[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Course Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Course"]
[Result "*"]

{ When I first started playing chess, I was extremely methodical with my learning. Following freely available beginner study plans on the internet, I conscientiously read the articles, watched the videos, and solved the puzzles sequentially as instructed. And at the end of the day, I would review everything I learnt on a notepad.  One of the key characteristics I developed from such intentional study was very principled opening play. I learnt core concepts like controlling the centre, developing rapidly, and keeping my King safe.  Feeling like an "educated" chess player, I was all ready to use my newly acquired knowledge to crush any opponent on chess.com. Little did I know that my naïve sense of invincibility was about to crumble.  Very often, there were opponents who violated every principle I knew, creating unnatural development schemes, negligently hurling their pawns at my King and somehow emerging victorious. Licking my wounds after such brutal defeats, I consulted an engine on why caveman-styled chess was beating a scholastic approach.  I often walked away confused. The engine claimed I could have played a certain mysterious move at some point in the game to gain a sizeable advantage.  To my 900-rated self, such advice from the engine felt completely arbitrary, and perhaps even counterintuitive. For example, a specific pawn push would be favoured over castling. Or, the computer would rather develop a Knight to the rim rather than the centre. Progress was uncertain.  Thankfully, some form of enlightenment came from helpful members of the chess community. I learnt that the rationale behind the suggested moves was based on positional considerations. Still, the fog of confusion was far from being lifted as I constantly had to guess the underlying concept. “Was this pawn push good because it controls the centre, or because it opens the position?” or “Was Nd2 better than Nc3 because the Knight belonged on f3 or because it doesn’t block our b2 Bishop?”  However, I soldiered on to play and analyse thousands more games. With each loss, I postulated why the engine didn’t like some of my moves and tested different strategies by playing the same positions against formidable chess bots. Unsurprisingly, I was thrashed by these merciless droids most of time. The cycle of losing-postulating-testing went on until I figured out the contexts in which different strategies worked. Over time, my understanding of chess grew stronger and my rating began to agree.   Although the journey was long and arduous, the fruit was sweet. I no longer have to waste time memorising the refutation to every bad chess opening. With my strategical understanding, I can often work out an answer over-the-board to punish my opponents as soon as they deviate from theory. This has also translated to an improved middlegame and endgame for myself.  Empathising with those who feel helpless against opponents who don’t conform to elementary chess principles, I created this course. Here, you will find great emphasis on strategies and how to truly understand the positional nature of chess. If you are able to punish dubious openings, you can keep the cavemen in their place.  As you go through the material, please analyse each game slowly and seriously. It is one thing to know the overarching strategies but another to execute them when the rubber meets the road. A 1400-rated player could tell you that controlling the centre is a good idea, but only someone like Magnus Carlsen could conduct it with such great care and precision.   With that said, I wish you all your best in your journey to mastering the opening phase and much more. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Basic Opening Principles"]
[Result "*"]

{ This chapter covers raw fundamentals that most players above 1200 online rating should be familiar with. However, to ensure a comprehensive understanding of these concepts, I implore you to go through this chapter in full. Understanding opening principles allows you to play sound chess in the first few moves. Additionally, you can identify dubious play from your opponents and hence punish them accordingly.   ------   I find many players spending a disproportionate amount of time aimlessly memorising opening traps, enthralled at the prospect of snatching a quick and effortless victory from an unsuspecting opponent. However, they will find themselves ensnaring few opponents while remaining clueless in the vast majority of unmemorised positions.  After all, the possibilities in chess increase exponentially to astronomical numbers very fast. There are 400 unique resulting positions after just the first move from both sides, and a whopping 197,742 possible games after move two. By the third move, this number skyrockets to about 121 million!  Therefore, for our chess study to be efficient and meaningful, we need to learn concepts that are applicable across a diverse set of positions. And what better way to do so than by simply mastering a few concepts with universal applications. So without further ado, let’s explore the three basic opening principles.  1.	Control the Centre  Good control over the centre effectively gives you the flexibility to bring your forces to any area of the board efficiently. Furthermore, the centre is a limited commodity – firm control over such a prime location deprives your opponent of it.  2.	Develop Actively and Rapidly  Chess is a race for just about everything, securing our King, hunting the opponent’s King, winning material, etc. A superior piece activity will facilitate this. This means players should make the most out of every single move, bringing all their troops to their best squares in the least amount of time.  3.	Keep the King safe  This is rather easy to understand – The goal of the game is to checkmate your opponent’s King, and by extension, keep your own safe. This principle nearly always entails castling, but as you will see in subsequent chapters, there are exceptions. }
