{ While those three basic principles are the core of any good opening, they are certainly not enough on their own to help anybody play a perfectly in the first few moves. Hence, the rest of the chapter will cover secondary principles derived from the basic three, illustrated with annotated examples.  To be clear, the examples may not necessarily have either side playing the best moves all the time. The moves are merely chosen to demonstrate the concepts. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Connect the Rooks"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqrbk1/pp3ppp/2p2n2/3p4/3P1B2/2NB1N1P/PPP2PP1/R2QR1K1 w - - 1 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Connect the Rooks@@HeaderEnd@@There are two reasons for this principle. Firstly, connecting the Rooks is a by-product of completing development and castling. Secondly, connected Rooks mutually defend each other to maintain control over an open file. In this example, both sides’ Rooks are staring at each other on the e-file, and it appears that the tension will be promptly resolved. However, thanks to White’s lead in development, he can keep the e-file all to himself just by connecting the Rooks. }
11. Qd2
{ It doesn't matter whether Black initiates the Rook trade. Either way, White's better coordinated Rooks will dominate the only open file. }
11... Rxe1+
{ If Black does not initiate the trade, White can trade the Rooks and swiftly swing the other Rook over to the open file.   11...Nbd7  12.Rxe8  Qxe8  13.Re1 }
12. Rxe1
{ After the trade, White's connected Rooks allow White to seamlessly maintain control over the file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Control the Centre with Pawns"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Control the Centre with Pawns@@HeaderEnd@@The lower a piece’s value, the more effectively it can control a square. This is because a high-value pieces can be easily displaced whereas low-value pieces often don’t need to move when attacked, but can simply be defended. Hence, the most reliable way to control the centre is with pawns rather than pieces. To illustrate, I will show a hypothetical game where both sides control the centre - White with pawns, and Black with pieces. }
1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 Nf6
{ Both sides have spent their first two moves controlling the centre. However, Black's control is far less secure than White's because the Knights are easily displaced. }
3. d5
{ Hitting the c6 Knight. Now Black has an unpleasant decision to make - to admit his Knight's development was premature and bring it back to b8, or to keep in the centre where it can be bossed around by the pawns further. Either way, White ends up with a significantly better centre. }
3... Nb8
{ 3...Na5  This allows White to win material  4.e5  Before trapping the Knight on a5 with b4, White should save the e4 pawn from the f6 Knight  4...Ng8  5.b4  Thanks to White's strategical dominance, the Black Knight has nowhere to run   3...Nb4  4.a3  Kicking the Knight to a worse square before pushing e5  4...Na6  5.e5  Ng8   3...Ne5  4.f4  Ng6  5.e5  Ng8 }
4. e5 Ng8
{ In all lines, White ends up with a stronger centre than he started out with on move 2 while Black false front is torn down. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Develop Knights to the Centre"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Develop Knights to the Centre@@HeaderEnd@@Knights are short-ranged pieces. Hence, they need to be near the centre to have any serious influence over the game. The following game demonstrates just that. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Both sides have correctly developed their Knights towards the centre. } 4.
Ng5
{ This opening is known as the Fried Liver Attack. White boldly strikes on f7 early in the game, which is only possible, again, because White's Knight was developed to the central f3 square. }
4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5
{ This move is a mistake due to tactical reasons as we will soon see. } 6. Nxf7
{ Drawing the King out. } 6... Kxf7 7. Qf3+
{ This is the point of the Knight sacrifice! For Black to preserve his material, he must move the King deeper into the centre to defend the d5 Knight. }
7... Ke6 8. Nc3
{ Again, White's remaining Knight can only avenge his brother by developing towards the centre and attacking d5. }
8... Nb4
{ Similarly, Black's development of his Knight to the central c6 square on move 2 allows this resource - defending d5 while counterattacking c2. Nevertheless, White still has more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed Knight because Black's King can't find a safe home.   In any case, the main point is that both sides only had the attacking and defensive resources they had because their Knights were well-developed in the centre. }
*

