[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Develop Bishops and Rooks to Open Lines"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Develop Bishops and Rooks to Open Lines@@HeaderEnd@@Unlike Knights, Bishops and Rooks are long-ranged pieces. So when identifying good development squares for them, the focus should not be placing them IN the centre, but finding good diagonals and files for them respectively. Assuming we have a free hand to make 6 developmental moves, how should you use them? }
4. Bd3
{ In some order, Bd3, Nf3, O-O, Re1, Bf4, and Nbd2/Nc3. This is because our Knights will be centralised, both our Bishops will have rather open diagonals, our King will be safe on g1, while our Rook will control the only open file.   Click here to see the final position -->  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P1B2/2NB1N2/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 b kq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@) }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Develop the Queen with Patience and Modesty"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Develop the Queen with Patience and Modesty@@HeaderEnd@@We should develop our Queen modestly in the opening. The reason is similar to why we control the centre with pawns - low-valued pieces offer firmer control over squares. By bringing out the Queen early and ambitiously, the opponent will be able to swiftly develop lower-valued pieces while attacking the Queen. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ With Black's Queen out this early, White is able to develop his Knight with tempo. Black would be wise to move the Queen to a stable square such as a5, d6, or even d8 where it cannot be easily attacked }
3... Qe5+
{ Forcing White to deal with the check, but it is hardly an inconvenience. White can develop while blocking the check. On the other hand, Black's Queen is still in the middle and will be kicked around some more. }
4. Be2 Nc6 5. Nf3
{ As mentioned earlier, the Queen needs to move again. Black should cut his losses and move the Queen to a5 or d6. }
5... Qf4 { Allowing itself to be attacked once more. } 6. d4
{ With a discovered attack from the g1 Bishop.  Note that   6.g3?  does not have the same impact. Although Black has to spend another tempo on the Queen, g3 isn't a very productive move for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "The Principle of Reciprocating Waste"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@The Principle of Reciprocating Waste@@HeaderEnd@@ Most of you would have heard that it is not ideal to move the same piece twice in the opening. The exception to this principle is when your opponent moves a single piece more than once. This is because recapturing or defending may now become necessary. Conversely, you may also choose to move the same piece twice if this forces your opponent to do likewise. We will explore this concept in the following game. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ Besides controlling the centre, this pawn move frees the dark-squared Bishop. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ Now it appears as though White is violating the principle of developing efficiently by moving the Knight twice @@StartBracket@@Nf3 and Nxd4@@EndBracket@@. However, Black had likewise invested two moves in the e-pawn @@StartBracket@@...e5 and ...exd4@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, Nxd4 is perfectly justified.   On the flip side, Black could afford to spend two moves on his e-pawn because he knew White would have had to move his Kingside Knight a second time to recapture }
4... Nxd4
{ Now Black is moving the Knight a second time, but because White can recapture and develop the Queen at the same time, White is now one move faster in development. }
5. Qxd4 Ne7 6. Nc3 Nc6
{ Moving this Knight a second time. However, this forces our Queen to likewise move a second time. Hence, Black's Ne7-c6 plan is principally sound. }
7. Qe3 Bb4 8. Bd2
{ Since Black has made one mistake, 4... Nxd4, while White's play was flawless, White has a lead in development and a moderate advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
