[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Castle Early"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Castle Early@@HeaderEnd@@Kings are generally unsafe in the centre because they are at the heart of the battlefield. In the following game, Alexander Alekhine vs Konstantin Isakov, Black got into serious trouble on move 21 for having remained uncastled up till that point! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 d5 4. Qa4 f6 5. Bb5 Ne7 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. O-O Bd7 8. d4
e4 9. Nfd2 f5 10. Nb3 Ne5 11. Nc5 c6 12. Be2 Bc8 { Defending b7 } 13. Be3 b5
14. Qa5 Nc4 15. Bxc4 Qxc4 16. Nd2 Qd5 17. a4 Ng6 18. f3 Bxc5 19. dxc5 Qd3 20.
Bg5 h6 { This was Black's last chance to save his King and castle   20...O-O }
21. Nxe4
{ Opening the centre! This concept of opening the centre will be explored further in a later chapter. }
21... hxg5
{ 21...O-O  Castling was the last chance to stay in the game.  22.Nf2  Qc2  23.Be3  Black would lose a pawn, but at least the King is safe.  23...Qxb2  24.Rfb1  and b5 falls.     21...dxe4  runs into  22.Rad1  White's pieces converging on the d8 square spells trouble for Black's King. }
22. Nd6+ Kd7 { 22...Kf8  23.Qd8 } 23. Rad1 Qe3+ 24. Kh1 Qf4 25. g3 Qxa4 26.
Ne4+
{ Alekhine played   26.Nxb5+  winning Black's queen, when Black immediately resigned. However, he could also have played the text move to mate Black. }
26... Ke6 { 26...Ke7  27.Qc7+  Ke6  28.Rd6+  Ke5  29.Qxg7 } 27. Rd6+ Ke5 28.
Qc7 Rg8 { Defending against Qxg7+   28...fxe4  29.Qxg7+  Kf5  30.Qf6 } 29. Rd7+
Ke6 30. Qd6# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
