[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Leave the f-pawn #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Leave the f-pawn #1@@HeaderEnd@@Moving the f-pawn in the opening without knowing what you are doing is a recipe for disaster. The f-pawn plays an extremely important role in defending the King along the h5-e8 diagonal for Black and the h4-e1 diagonal for White. We'll see one of the many reasons this diagonal is critical in the following line. }
1. d4 f5 { Moving the f-pawn and exposing the h5-e8 diagonal. } 2. Bg5
{ Pinning the e-pawn. The plan with this move is to provoke further weaknesses on the kingside. }
2... h6 3. Bh4 g5 { Black unknowingly cooperates with White's plan. } 4. e3
{ Hanging the Bishop? } 4... gxh4 5. Qh5#
{ Nope, it's mate. Notice how Black's Kingside pieces are not in a position to block the h5-e8 diagonal. Therefore, the responsibility of guarding the diagonal rests almost entirely on the f-pawn. Now, you might be thinking that it was moving both the f- AND the g-pawns in this game that was Black's doing. However, as you will see from the following examples, moving the f-pawn while keeping the g-pawn at home can still prove risky. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Leave the f-pawn #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Leave the f-pawn #2@@HeaderEnd@@Here's a famous game by Greco playing with the White pieces. }
1. e4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 f5
{ Trying to deflect the e-pawn so that the b7 Bishop can take on g2 and trap the h1 Rook. However, Black could not afford to move the f-pawn in this position because he was far too underdeveloped to protect his weakened King. }
4. exf5 Bxg2
{ Greco's opponent jumps at this opportunity to seemingly win some material. }
5. Qh5+ { Forcing Black to play g6 and further weaken his kingside. } 5... g6
6. fxg6 Nf6 7. gxh7+ { Queen sacrifice! } 7... Nxh5 8. Bg6#
{ Yet again, we see the same type of checkmate along this soft diagonal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Leave the f-pawn #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Leave the f-pawn #3@@HeaderEnd@@This is a rated 3+0 blitz game on lichess between two players rated about 2500. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6 { The f-pawn needed to stay behind and guard Black's King. }
3. Nxe5 { Softening e5 and clearing the way for Qh5+. } 3... fxe5 4. Qh5+ Ke7
{ 4...g6  This is the only other legal move and it loses a Rook.  5.Qxe5+  Qe7  6.Qxh8  Qxe4+  7.Kd1 }
5. Qxe5+ { The start of White's decisive attack. } 5... Kf7 6. Bc4+
{ Adding yet another attacker. Black's King will not survive. } 6... Kg6 7.
Qf5+ Kh6 8. d4+ { White brings their dark-squared Bishop to the party. } 8...
g5 9. h4 { The h-pawn and the h1 Rook are here too! } 9... Be7 10. hxg5+ Kg7
11. Qf7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Fundamental Principles"]
[Black "Leave the f-pawn #4"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Leave the f-pawn #4@@HeaderEnd@@Here's another game from lichess. Both players were rated over 2000 in this 10+0 rapid game. }
1. e4 d5 2. e5 c5 3. d4 Nc6 4. c3 e6 5. Bd3 f6 6. Qh5+ g6 7. Bxg6+
{ This is yet another tactical resource to look out for when the f-pawn is moved - The Bishop is immune to capture because the h7 pawn is pinned to the h8 Rook.  Black resigned  (somewhat prematurely)  here in view of   7.Bxg6+  hxg6  8.Qxh8 }
