[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the 'Dubious or Not?' Quiz! In each exercise, you will be shown an unannotated game and must evaluate the quality of play of both sides using one of five descriptions:  1. Perfect  (Approx. advantage loss: 0.0 to 0.2)   No mistakes, completely sound, and suitable for a repertoire for the World Championships.  2. Good  (Approx. advantage loss: 0.2 to 0.5)   At the highest level, this opening variation may not be the most testing, but is still taken seriously.  3. Off Beat  (Approx. advantage loss: 0.5 to 1.0)   Off beat openings often vaguely violate some opening principles without compromising the position significantly. The idea is to avoid mainline theory and set up traps. Such openings are occasionally seen at the master level, but almost never seen in elite tournaments such as the Candidates.  4. Dubious  (Approx. advantage loss: 1.0 to 2.0)   Dubious openings clearly violate chess principles and one can almost never get away against master-level opposition. If your opponent plays such an opening, you should be on the lookout for a knockout blow.  5. Wrong  (Approx. advantage loss: 2.0 and above)   Often played by new players, wrong openings immediately concede an obvious advantage to the opponent. }
