[White "2. Dubious or Not?"]
[Black "The Subjectivity of Evaluation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. --
{ If you are only slightly off in your assessment in any of the following positions, do not be disheartened. Unlike many other aspects of chess, evaluation has some room for subjectivity. Take this position for example, where Black is missing the b8 Knight.  If you asked a 200-rated player for their evaluation, they might say that White is only slightly better because a full piece is almost irrelevant at this level.  A 1000-rated player might say +3, since a Knight's nominal value is 3 points.  An 1800-rated player might say + 3.5, given that White also has the first move, which starts to matter a bit at this level.  A 2600-rated GM might say +4.5. After all, not only does White have a material advantage, they have a positional advantage with one extra attacker.  Finally, an omniscient chess engine would see all the way to the end and declare mate in 56.  Who's to say who is right? Objectively speaking, the omniscient chess engine is the most correct. But to a human chess player, describing this position as mate in x is not particularly helpful. It doesn't do justice to the potential complexity of the position, and the potential for White to blunder.  Meaningful chess evaluation is, therefore, a reflection of your confidence in converting the position and should vary slightly depending on your skill level. Of course, you would need to be in the ballpark of the engine's assessment  (If the engine says White is winning by +2, it is wrong to say that the position is equal)  .  With that, I wish you all the best for this exercise! }
*

