[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Dubious or Not?"]
[Black "Exercise #1 - Answer"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ This is rarely seen in elite tournaments because it does not control the centre directly with pawns. Nonetheless, it is a principled opening - White will put the Bishop on b2 where it is active and exerting great pressure on the central dark squares. }
1... d5 { Black correctly puts a pawn in the centre. } 2. Bb2 Bg4
{ An interesting move. Black pins White's e-pawn, making it rather inconvenient for White to get their light-squared Bishop out. The downside is that Black may be better off focusing on centre control or more natural piece development instead.   2...c5   2...Nf6 }
3. h3 Bh5
{ Both sides mutually 'waste' one tempo on their h-pawn and Bishop respectively. Hence, neither side has come out worse from the h3-Bh5 shuffle. }
4. Nf3 Bxf3 5. exf3
{ Let's weigh the pros on cons of this trade. Both sides have lost one developed piece and one tempo on the capture. However, White's recapture has conveniently liberated the light-squared Bishop. The only downside is that Black still has better centre control. Hence, the game remains fairly balanced - Black must spend an extra move liberating their dark-squared Bishop while White must spend an extra move to match Black's centre control, and that's how the game proceeded. }
5... e6 6. f4
{ Controlling the centre without blocking the dark-squared Bishop. } 6... Nf6
7. g3
{ Investing more time into the centre, thereby limiting Black's dark-squared Bishop.   7.Bd3  If White had developed the Bishop directly, they would still need another move to consolidate their f4 pawn.  7...Bd6  8.g3  At this point, we can clearly see that White's light-squared Bishop belongs on g2. }
7... Be7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ Final verdict: Both sides' play was GOOD. White could have opened the game by putting a pawn in the centre while Black could have developed more naturally instead of going for the funky ...Bg4 idea. I would not be surprised to see two 2200+ FIDE rated players playing this line. }
