1. e4 e6 { Preparing the challenge White's e4 pawn with the d5 pawn push. } 2.
d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 { Both sides spend a move to capture on d5. } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5.
Bd3 Bg4
{ By developing a Queenside piece, Black delays castling slightly. As a result, they must contend with minor inconveniences on the open e-file. }
6. O-O Be7
{ Solving the uncastled King's problem on the e-file at the cost of the some piece activity - d6 is a much more active square for the dark-squared Bishop. }
7. Bf4
{ Since Black did not put their Bishop on d6, White uses this active diagonal for his own. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. Re1 Re8
{ Both sides brought their Knights and Rooks to active posts. Final verdict: White's play was PERFECT while Black's play was GOOD. This is reflected in the slight difference in piece activity. }
