8. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 9. Nd2 Bxe5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Dubious or Not?"]
[Black "Exercise #3 - Answer"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5 { Giving up a full pawn for negligible compensation can't be good. }
2. dxe5 Nc6 3. Nf3 Qe7 4. Bf4
{ Black tries to regain their pawn with the last two moves, but White correctly defends while developing. As long as White's development is not compromised in maintaining the material advantage, White would be better. }
4... Qb4+ 5. Bd2
{ Black spends a second move on their Queen while White does the same with the dark-squared Bishop. However, Black's Queen is now attacked and must move yet another time. }
5... Qxb2 6. Nc3
{ Developing rapidly while amply covering the a5-e1 diagonal and fortifying the first rank.   6.Bc3??  This is probably Black's only trick. If White plays Bc3 here, Black can exploit White's various weaknesses with ...  6...Bb4!  White has issues with their hanging a1 Rook, hanging c3 Bishop, and soft c2 and c1 squares.  7.Bxb4   7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  The only way to defend the Rook, but this leaves c1 unattended.  8...Qc1  Nxb4  The threats are Nxc2 and Qxa1 }
6... Bb4 7. Rb1
{ Developing the Rook to a half-open file while forcing Black to move the Queen for the fourth time. }
7... Qxc3 { If Black sacrifices their Queen, it can't get chased around. } 8.
Bxc3 Bxc3+ 9. Nd2 Bxe5
{ At the end of the day, Black only has two pieces and a pawn for the Queen while development remains fairly equal. Final verdict: White's play was PERFECT while Black's play was just WRONG. }
