{ White gambits a pawn to develop efficiently on the Queenside. } 3... d5
{ An opportune time to strike at the centre. I will explain after 4...Qxd5.   3...bxa3  Taking the pawn accepts the sacrifice on White's terms. This is because Black is the one spending a move capturing while White is conveniently developing and recapturing.  4.Bxa3 }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black has gotten rid of White's central e4 pawn. The downside to such a trade is that Black's Queen is left vulnerable on d5. However, in this case, not only is White unable to kick it with Nc3, Black is threatening Qe5+ to fork the King and Rook. }
5. Nf3 { Stopping Qe5+. } 5... e5 6. Bb2 Nc6
{ Both sides increase their influence over the central dark squares, but it remains that White will be down a pawn. Overall, White's play is OFF BEAT while Black's play is PERFECT. }
