[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Indirectly controlling the centre by pressuring the c6 Knight. } 3... a6 4.
Ba4
{ Both sides mutually waste a move on the Queenside.   4.Bxc6  This does not win the e5 pawn because White's own e4 pawn is undefended.  4...dxc6  5.Nxe5  Qd4  Black is forking the e5 Knight and e4 pawn and will equalise material. }
4... Nf6 5. O-O
{ White indirectly defends e4 by preparing the put his Rook on e1, opposite Black's uncastled King. }
5... Be7 { Closing the e-file and preparing the castle. } 6. Re1
{ 6.Bxc6  Yet again, this does not win a pawn because White's e4 pawn is a problem.  6...dxc6  7.Nxe5  Nxe4  Black can castle shortly and will have no problems along the e-file. }
6... b5 7. Bb3
{ Again, both sides mutually delay development for one move with ...b5 and Bb3. }
7... d6 8. c3
{ Delaying development in the short run for the greater good. Once White gets to play d4, they would have a solid centre and good squares for all their pieces.   8.Nc3  For example, if White eagerly brought his Knight out to c3, then White's c-pawn is deprived of the c3 square. This means Black can put their Knight on d4.  8...Bg4  9.h3  Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Nd4  Black has an excellent central Knight. }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Preventing ...Bg4 so that the d4 pawns defence cannot be easily undermined. This is 9 moves of perfect opening theory which of course means both sides' play was PERFECT. }
