2... exf4
{ Black is now threatening Qh4+. We have seen this pattern before here. The typical way to combat it is to go Nf3. }
3. Bc4 { By vacating the f1 square, White takes the sting out of Qh4+. } 3...
Nf6
{ 3...Qh4+  4.Kf1  White's King is not in any serious danger and Black's Queen must move again after Nf3. }
4. Nc3 c6 { Preparing to fight for the centre with d5. } 5. Bb3
{ Prophylactically getting the Bishop out of the way. Black is likely to play ...d5 regardless. }
5... d5 6. exd5 cxd5 7. d4 { Maintaining a stake in the centre. } 7... Bb4 8.
Nf3 O-O { 8...Qe7+  Can be conveniently met with  9.Ne5 } 9. O-O
{ 9.O-O  Bxc3  10.bxc3  Qc7  Black pressures c3 while making it difficult for White to regain their pawn on f4. This inconvenience gives Black the advantage, although White has better attacking chances. Overall, White's play is OFF BEAT while Black's play is PERFECT. }
