1... e5 2. c3
{ A very awkward way to defend b4. Typically, White would want their dark-squared Bishop on b2, but now the a1-h8 diagonal is closed. }
2... d5 3. a3
{ White overprotects b4 so that the c3 pawn is free to support the d4 push. }
3... Nf6 4. d4 Nbd7
{ Developing the Queenside Knight while defending e5.   4...exd4  5.cxd4  This line shows the usefulness of 3. a3. b4 is now defended. }
5. dxe5 Nxe5 { Both sides spend one move on the to capture on e5. } 6. Nf3
{ White finally develops a piece. } 6... Bd6
{ Similar to 4...Nbd7, Black develops while defending. } 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bb2
{ The Bishop can make itself useful after pushing c4. Overall, White's play was dubious for only the first two moves, but that is enough to give Black a moderate advantage. Overall, White's play was DUBIOUS while Black's play was PERFECT. }
