1. d4 f5
{ This move controls e4 and the idea is to push the f-pawn before putting the Kingside Knight on f6. This is rarely seen in elite tournaments but Black should be fine as long as they don't allow any tactical tricks. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O
{ Both sides efficiently get their pieces out while investing an extra, non-developing move on centre control. White played c4 while Black played f5. }
6. Nc3 d6
{ Black liberates the light-squared Bishop while preparing further centre control with ...e5. }
7. O-O Ne4
{ Black attempts to further their centre control. If the e4 Knight is taken, Black will have three pawns in the centre and a half-open f-file. }
8. Qc2
{ Developing the Queen modestly while hitting the e4 Knight.   8.Nxe4  fxe4  9.Nd2  d5 }
8... Nxc3 9. Qxc3
{ Both sides spend a move trading Knights on c3. White holds a slight advantage thanks to their stronger centre control and ability to expand on the Queenside. However, Black has better attacking chances thanks to his slight space advantage on the Kingside, but it is nothing too scary. Overall, White's play was PERFECT while Black's play was GOOD. }
