1. d4 e6 2. e4 d5
{ White grabbed the centre, and Black challenged it with a well-supported ...d5 push. }
3. Nd2
{ White defends the e4 pawn with their Knight while ensuring that it cannot be pinned.   3.Nc3  This defends the e4 pawn but the Knight can be pinned.  3...Bb4  Black renews the pressure on e4. }
3... Nf6 { Attacking e4 again. } 4. e5 Nfd7
{ Both sides spend an extra tempo on their e-pawn and Knight respectively. } 5.
c3
{ Prophylactically defending d4 since White knows that Black will play ...c5 eventually. The concept is similar to what we saw with Bb3 in Exercise 7. }
5... c5 6. Bd3 { The Bishop's best square. } 6... Nc6
{ The Knight's best square. } 7. Ne2
{ Keeping the f3 vacant for the d2 Knight. The e2 Knight can activate on f4 or g3 instead.   7.Ngf3  White's two Knights are now competing for the same square, f3. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 f6
{ A risky way to challenge the centre, but White has no good tactics. } 9. Nf4
{ The trickiest move. The threats are Qh5+ and Nxe6. } 9... Nxd4
{ Black defends e6. } 10. Qh5+ Ke7 11. exf6+ Nxf6 12. Ng6+
{ Forking King and Rook. } 12... hxg6 13. Qxh8 Kf7
{ Black defends the g6 pawn. Let's evaluate the final position. Black is down a small amount of material - Knight and pawn for a Rook. However, they have a significantly stronger centre and could look to go ...e5 and ...e4. Furthermore, Black's King is not in any serious danger because it is well-surrounded by its own pieces. Overall, the position is competitive and both sides' play was PERFECT. }
