[White "2. Dubious or Not?"]
[Black "Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now that we are able to better identify dubious opening play, it is time to move on to the bigger problem: How do we punish it?   To answer this question, we will need to learn four important strategic ideas. Each idea will have its own chapter containing a few instructional games. In the final section of the course, we will bring all four ideas together and work on exercises based on 15 games played across all levels. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Identifying and Attacking Targets"]
[Black "Chapter Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ The first and most fundamental concept to punishing bad openings is identifying targets. There are two fundamental types of targets - Tactical and Strategical.   Tactical targets refer to those that can yield us short-term gains. For example, unprotected or trappable pieces. These tactics are nearly always obvious with the aid of an engine. Furthermore, this is under the domain of calculation, which I discuss in great detail in my first course on Chessable, Calculation: A Complete Guide for Tournament Players. Hence, my focus will be on strategical targets, which is something that engines cannot explicitly tell you.  Essentially, strategical targets refer to long-term weaknesses that are more permanent, and hence share a close relationship with the permanent nature of pawn structures. A target can be a weak pawn, a weak square, an open file, or even an unsafe King that cannot easily run to safety. Such targets are often inevitable products of dubious play.  Once a strategical target is identified, our whole army will have a common long-term goal and can progress with intention and coordination.  We will see a few examples of this in the following games, with analyses primarily focused on the opening. After each game, we will review the key moments in 'puzzle' format. As you go through the puzzles, be sure to remind yourself of why the text move is best instead of just thoughtlessly playing from memory. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Identifying and Attacking Targets"]
[Black "Game #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ For this first game, I have selected a casual OTB rapid game I played with a ~1600 FIDE opponent. I had the Black pieces. }
1. d4 e6 2. e4 d5 3. e5 c5
{ A necessary pawn break to not only have a stronger centre, but also to attack d4 }
4. c3
{ My opponent correctly reinforces d4   4.dxc5?!  If White ever captures on c5, White will lose an important central pawn and e5 will be much weaker.  4...Bxc5 }
4... Nc6
{ Since dxc5 is always less than ideal for White, the pawn on d4 is here to stay. Therefore, this is the long-term target which I should bring my forces to. }
5. f4
{ Reinforcing e5 well before it is even necessary. White's move would have been better spent developing and defending d4.   5.Nf3  White can promptly play Be2 and castle short }
5... Qb6
{ Punishing White's slow f4 move by going straight for our main target, d4. }
6. Nf3 Nh6
{ The Knight is heading to f5 to attack d4! With the pawn on f4, there is no need to worry about Bxh6. Furthermore, it was best to avoid ...Ne7 which blocks the dark-squared Bishop. }
7. a3
{ Not a productive move. In any case, White doesn't have a good move to defend d4   7.Na3  White is planning to defend the d4 weakness with Nc2. Hence, we must get rid of it ahead of time.  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Bxa3  9.bxa3  Nf5  Now d4 will certainly fall.   7.Be3  Defends d4 but drops b2.  7...Qxb2 }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Forcing White's pawn to d4, where it will be an easy target. } 9. cxd4 Nf5
{ d4 now belongs to Black. } 10. Nc3 Bd7
{ Before capturing on d4, Black played this somewhat thematic move, which stops both Bb5+ and Na4. Additionally, the plan is to activate the Bishop with ...Bb5 in the future. }
11. g4
{ Unnecessarily weakening the squares around White's King. Black's Knight is headed to d4 anyway.   11.Ne2  If White tried to defend the pawn, he will be even further behind in development. The plan was ...h5 to secure the f5 Knight's home and then Bb5 to activate the 'bad' light-squared Bishop. And at any point, Black can play Bb5xe2 and win d4.  11...h5  12.g3  Bb5 }
11... Nxd4 12. Qd3 Be7
{ Since g4 was played, a new weakness is the h4-e1 diagonal. The idea is to harrass White's King and force it to lose the right to castle. }
13. b4 Rc8
{ X-raying the c2 square and pressuring the c3 Knight now that it doesn't have the b2 pawn defending it. }
14. Bb2 Bh4+
{ White has a very unsafe King, is significantly less active, has multiple weaknesses, and is down a pawn. The rest is a matter of technique for Black. }
15. Kd1 Nb3 16. Rb1 Qf2 17. Be2 Qxf4 18. Nxd5
{ It might appear that Black has blundered the discovered attack on the b3 Knight. }
18... exd5 19. Qxb3 Qe4
{ Forking two Rooks. The game is over.   Conclusion: White opened with a dubious 5. f4, a rather slow move. The only way for Black to punish it was by identifying and attacking a clear target @@StartBracket@@i.e. the d4 pawn@@EndBracket@@ to accentuate Black's superior development. After winning d4, Black could continue the initiative by identifying new targets, such as the h4-e1 diagonal, and working towards them. }
