[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Identifying and Attacking Targets"]
[Black "Game #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ The next game is between John Bartholomew  (1078)  and Paul Mattione  (1136)  played back in 1999. Even though John was barely rated over 1000, he played a really principled and instructive game. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5
{ We have the Exchange variation of the French Defence on board. } 4. Bd3 c5
{ Similar to the previous game, Black is striking at the centre with ...c5, so White responds with c3 to reinforce it. }
5. c3 c4
{ Black concedes the pressure on d4 to gain more space on the Queenside. However, White can easily undermine the c4 pawn with a b2-b3 pawn break. }
6. Bc2
{ Both White's light-squared Bishop and Black's c-pawn have moved twice already. By the principle of reciprocating waste, neither side is behind in development. }
6... b5
{ This move reinforces c4, but does not help Black with his piece activity or King safety. }
7. Nf3 Nc6
{ Normally, developing the queenside Knight to one of its favourite squares cannot be wrong. However, in this instance, White is well ahead in development and wants to castle and immediately take advantage of the e-file. Hence, Black's priority should be to develop kingside pieces and castle as early as possible. }
8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1+
{ White correctly identifies the main target here to be the e-file. } 9... Be6
{ After this move, what is the main target?   9...Be7  What if Black had played Be7? What would be the main target?   The target would be e7. One of White's plans should be to pressure e7 to tie the Black King to its defence. This will stop Black from castling. However, as it is, e7 is well-protected with three defenders - c6 Knight, d8 Queen, and e8 King, and is only attacked once by White's e1 Rook. This means 10. Qe2 is not sufficient - Black would simply castle.  10.Ne5  Therefore, the best move is Ne5, harassing the c6 Knight, not giving Black time to castle. Black has two options: Capture on e5 or defend c6. We will explore both   10...Nxe5  11.dxe5  Taking with the Rook would lose the initiative since Black could simply castle. But now, with White's pawn on e5, the Black Knight has no good squares.  11...Ng4  12.e6  Interfering with the c8 Bishop's defence to the g4 Knight.  12...Bxe6  13.Rxe6  fxe6  14.Qxg4  Both e6 and g7 are hanging  10...Qc7  11.Nxc6  Of course, we remove the defender of e7.  11...Qxc6  12.a4  A useful zwischenzug before playing Qe2. The threat is to take on b5. If Black's Queen recaptures on b5, White will have the Ba4 pin.   12.Qe2?  This would be a good move if not for Black's one trick  12...O-O !  Now that our e1 Rook does not have the f3 Knight to defend it, it is more vulnerable to tactics.  13.Qxe7??  Re8  A neat skewer.  12...a6  13.Qe2  With the inclusion of a4 and ...a6, This move now works.  13...Be6  It's a good idea to try and close the e-file to allow castling.   13...O-O ??  14.axb5  axb5  15.Rxa8  Forcing Black's Queen away from the defence of the e8 square.  15...Qxa8  16.Qxe7  Black no longer has ...Re8  14.axb5  axb5  15.Rxa8+  Qxa8  16.Bf5  The targets is the e-file, and specifically, e6 and e7, so this is the only logical move! With the pin along the file, White will win AT LEAST a pawn.  16...Qc6  17.Bxe6  Qxe6  18.Qxe6  fxe6  19.Rxe6 }
10. Ng5
{ A simple but strong move. The main target has shifted from the e-file to specifically e6. White's subsequent moves should centre around attacking e6 or removing its defenders. }
10... Qd7 11. Bf5 { Adding attackers } 11... Nd8 12. Qe2
{ Adding another attacker } 12... Ke7 13. b3
{ Clearly, John was severely underrated. The idea is Ba3+. As a bonus, White has a slightly more pressure on c4. }
13... Ne8 { Preparing to block the check with ...Nd6. } 14. Ba3+ Nd6 15. f4
{ The f-pawn is ready to participate. The plan is to have White's Bishop vacate f5 and allow f4-f5! }
15... g6 16. Bh3 Bg7 17. Nd2
{ The queenside Knight is ready to follow his brother's footsteps with the maneuver Nb1-Nd2-Nf3-Ng5-Ne6. }
17... h6 18. Nxe6 Nxe6 19. Nf3
{ White's two Bishops are pinning Black's two Knights here and Black's King is still in the centre. John converted this advantage and won in another 50+ moves. }
19... Rhf8 20. Ne5 Qc8 21. Nxg6+ Kd8 22. Nxf8 Bxf8 23. Bxe6 Qxe6 24. Qxe6 fxe6
25. Rxe6 Kd7 26. Rg6 Re8 27. Bxd6 Bxd6 28. g3 b4 29. cxb4 c3 30. Kf2 Bxb4 31.
a3 Ba5 32. Rxh6 Bb6 33. Rxb6 axb6 34. Rc1 Re4 35. Rxc3 Rxd4 36. Ke3 Re4+ 37.
Kf3 Re7 38. Rd3 Kd6 39. h4 Ra7 40. b4 Rd7 41. g4 Kc6 42. g5 Kb5 43. f5 Kc4 44.
Ke2 Re7+ 45. Kd2 Re4 46. h5 d4 47. Rf3 Rg4 48. Rf2 Rg3 49. g6 Rxa3 50. g7 Ra2+
51. Kc1 Rxf2 52. g8=Q+ Kxb4 53. Qf8+ Kc3 54. Qa3+ Kc4 55. Qg3 Rxf5 56. h6 Rh5
57. h7 b5 58. Qg8+ Kc3 59. h8=Q Rxh8 60. Qxh8 b4 61. Qh3+ Kc4 62. Kc2 Kc5 63.
Kb3 Kb5 64. Qh5+ Kc6 65. Kxb4 d3 66. Qf3+ Kd6 67. Qxd3+ Ke5 68. Kc5 Kf4 69. Kd5
Kg5 70. Qf3 Kg6 71. Ke5 Kg7 72. Qf6+ Kh7 73. Qg5 Kh8 74. Kf6 Kh7 75. Qg7#
{ Conclusion: Since the e-pawns were traded early and Black did not castle, the key strategical target was the e-file. Subsequently, when White played Re1+, any piece blocking the file would become the pinned, and therefore permanent, strategical target. From there, it is all about bringing White's remaining pieces to that critical target. }
