[SetUp "1"]

{ What if Black had played 9...Be7? What would be the main target? } 10. Ne5
{ The target would be e7. One of White's plans should be to pressure e7 to tie the Black King to its defence. This will stop Black from castling. However, as it is, e7 is well-protected with three defenders - c6 Knight, d8 Queen, and e8 King, and is only attacked once by White's e1 Rook. This means 10. Qe2 is not sufficient - Black would simply castle.   Therefore, the best move is Ne5, harassing the c6 Knight, not giving Black time to castle. Black has two options: Capture on e5 or defend c6. We will explore both }
10... Nxe5
{ 10...Qc7  11.Nxc6  Of course, we remove the defender of e7.  11...Qxc6  12.a4  A useful zwischenzug before playing Qe2. The threat is to take on b5. If Black's Queen recaptures on b5, White will have the Ba4 pin.   12.Qe2?  This would be a good move if not for Black's one trick.  12...O-O !  Now that our e1 Rook does not have the f3 Knight to defend it, it is more vulnerable to tactics.  13.Qxe7??  Re8  A neat skewer.  12...a6  13.Qe2  With the inclusion of a4 and ...a6, this move now works..  13...Be6  It's a good idea to try and close the e-file to allow castling.   13...O-O ??  14.axb5  Qxb5  15.Qxe7  Re8  16.Qxe8+  Nxe8  17.Ba4!  Thanks to 12.a4, we have this skewer at the end. Black will either hang the Queen or back rank mate.  14.axb5  axb5  15.Rxa8+  Qxa8  16.Bf5  The targets is the e-file, and specifically, e6 and e7, so this is the only logical move ! With the pin along the file, White will win AT LEAST a pawn. }
11. dxe5
{ Taking with the Rook would lose the initiative since Black could simply castle. But now, with White's pawn on e5, the Black Knight has no good squares. }
11... Ng4 12. e6 { Interfering with the c8 Bishop's defence to the g4 Knight. }
12... Bxe6 13. Rxe6 fxe6 14. Qxg4 { Both e6 and g7 are hanging } *

