[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Identifying and Attacking Targets"]
[Black "Game #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ For our last game of the chapter, we have Mikhail Tal  playing White against Wolfgang Uhlmann. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 { The Tarrasch variation of the French Defence. } 3...
c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Bd7 7. Bg5 Qa5+ 8. Nc3
{ This retreat is forced since the b5 Bishop was hanging. } 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
Bb4
{ Black is threatening to win a pawn on c3 at the cost of a few moves. What is the best response? }
10. O-O
{ Defending c3 was possible, but Tal correctly decided focus on rapid development and ignore his material.   If Black wants to win a mere pawn on c3, he must give up the dark-squared Bishop, weakening the entire colour complex significantly. }
10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc3
{ Black may have won a pawn, but at what cost? White is even further ahead in development and has two main targets.   The first is the d6 square - Black no longer has a dark-squared Bishop to watch over this weakness!   The second target is the Black King which still needs some time to castle. Bearing these two soft spots in mind, Tal found a brilliant move. }
12. Nf5
{ Either the Knight lands on d6, or the e-file opens up. Black must pick his poison. }
12... exf5 13. Re1+ { Immediately making use of the newly opened e-file. }
13... Be6
{ Black closes the e-file, and plans to consolidate his material advantage with moves like ...Nf6 and ...O-O. How should White maintain the initiative? What is Black's weakness in this position?   13...Nge7  14.Rxe7+!  The c6 Knight is pinned to the d7 Bishop.  14...Nxe7  15.Qxd7+  Kf8  16.Bxe7+  Kg8  17.Rd1  Threatening a back rank mate.  17...h6  Creating a flight square for the King.  18.Qxb7  White has two Bishops for a Rook and is significantly more active. No player will stand a chance against Tal in this position! }
14. Qd6
{ Making Black regret giving up the dark-squared Bishop. Given that the c6 Knight is pinned, the duty of defending against Qe7# now rests solely on the Black g8 Knight. }
14... a6
{ Black understands that in many lines, the b5 Bishop is doing a great job pinning the c6 Knight, so he tries to kick it. At the same time, White cannot take on c6 because the Black Queen will recapture and defend his majesty. So, for the last time, what other weaknesses are there in Black's camp?   14...Nf6  What if Black had played ...Nf6? What is the threat here and how can we combat it?  15.Rad1!  Stopping the threat of ...Rd8  15...Rd8??  16.Qxd8  Again, the c6 Knight is pinned. }
15. Bd2
{ Black's main weakness is the weak dark squares! In particular, the e7 and f8 squares. That is why Tal is rerouting his dark-squared Bishop to b4. }
15... Qxc2 16. Bb4
{ 16.Rac1??  Black is already up a minor piece and two pawns. Hence, they can simply parry this attack by giving up the Queen for the c1 Rook, then take the b5 Bishop.  16...Qxc1  17.Rxc1  axb5  Black has two pawn, two Knights, and a Rook for the Queen.  18.Rxc6  White can try this one trick.  18...Rd8  Of course, Black doesn't take the c6 Rook and allow White to play 19. Qxc6+ with a fork. Now, all of White's pieces are effectively hanging and Black will maintain their material advantage. }
16... axb5
{ 16...Nf6  Defends f8 with the h8 Rook but this hangs mate on e7.  17.Qe7 }
17. Qf8+ Kd7 18. Red1+ Kc7 19. Qxa8
{ Black resigned here because White's pieces are very active whereas Black's kingside is congested. Furthermore, Black cannot even capture on b4 because of mate.   Conclusion: Black gave up his dark-squared Bishop and several tempi to take a pawn on c3. As a result, the d6 square was impossible to defend and Black's King was also well behind schedule in castling. All that was left was for White to open more lines to the enemy King and identify specific dark squares  (such as e7 and f8)  to exploit.   19.Qxa8  Nxb4  20.Qd8+  Kc6  21.Qd6 }
*

