[White "3. Identifying and Attacking Targets"]
[Black "Puzzle 3.4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k1nr/1p3ppp/p1nQb3/1B3pB1/8/2q5/P1P2PPP/R3R1K1 w kq - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black understands that in many lines, the b5 Bishop is doing a great job pinning the c6 Knight, so he tries to kick it with 14...a6. At the same time, White cannot take on c6 because the Black Queen will recapture and defend his majesty. So, for the last time, what other weaknesses are there in Black's camp? }
15. Bd2
{ Black's main weakness is the weak dark squares ! In particular, the e7 and f8 squares. That is why Tal is rerouting his dark-squared Bishop to b4. }
15... Qxc2 16. Bb4
{ 16.Rac1??  Black is already up a minor piece and two pawns. Hence, they can simply parry this attack by giving up the Queen for the c1 Rook, then take the b5 Bishop.  16...Qxc1  17.Rxc1  axb5  Black has two pawn, two Knights, and a Rook for the Queen.  18.Rxc6  White can try this one trick.  18...Rd8  Of course, Black doesn't take the c6 Rook and allow White to play 19. Qxc6+ with a fork. Now, all of White's pieces are effectively hanging and Black will maintain their material advantage. }
16... axb5 17. Qf8+ { White can play Rd1+ next or Qxa8. The game is over. } *

