15. Rad1
{ Black is trying to defend their d6 weakness by playing ...Rd8. Hence, we must stop it.     15.Bd2??  Ne4!  16.Rxe4  Qxa1  17.Re1  Qxe1  18.Bxe1  Rd8  Black has sufficient material for the Queen and has wiped out a good number of our attacking pieces. }
15... Rd8 16. Qxd8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Opening the Position"]
[Black "Chapter Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ If you play sound chess while your opponent plays inferior moves in the opening, you can expect better piece development than your opponent’s. However, if all 16 pawns are still on the board, your pieces will remain blocked and far from their full potential. Hence, the only logical way forward is to open up the position by trading pawns. With the pawns no longer blocking your pieces and concealing your opponent’s weaknesses, it will be easy to tactically punish your opponent for their poor strategic play. We’ll explore some model games in the next pages that demonstrate this concept. Again, please note that these analysis will focus primarily on the opening. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Opening the Position"]
[Black "Game #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Here is the first example on Opening the Position, a 5+0 blitz game between shapiro132_Leo playing White against GM Daniel Naroditsky playing Black as part of the American Grandmaster's Chess Speedrun series. }
1. d4 g6 2. b3
{ White is trying to fianchetto their Bishop but it is already a dubious start. White's dark-squared Bishop clearly does not belong on b2 since it will be blocked by the d4 pawn and Black will call dibs on the soft a1-h8 diagonal first with ...Bg7.   Furthermore, with an already open c1-h6 diagonal to develop the Bishop, there is no need to spend another move to open another diagonal for the same Bishop. }
2... Bg7 3. a3
{ Another slow move. We can consider Black to be doing better now. } 3... Nf6
{ 3...c5  Black could also go for c5 to open up the position and exacerbateWhite's weakness along the long a1-h8 diagonal  4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  d5  Black can plan on striking the centre with moves like ...Nc6 and ...Nh6-f5.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/3p1n2/3P4/PP6/2P2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  After that,  4.c3  will NOT completely save White because Black can try to open the diagonal with an  4...e5  pawn break. }
4. Bb2 O-O 5. Nd2 d6 6. Ngf3 Nbd7 7. e3 e5
{ White is two moves away from castling while Black's f8 Rook is ready to activate along any file that opens up. Hence, Naroditsky chose the e5 pawn break to punish White's uncastled King. }
8. e4
{ Wasting yet another move and allowing Black to open the e-file.   Black does NOT lose a pawn to dxe5 because of a thematic tactic   8.dxe5  Ng4  Unleashing a pin from g7 to b2 and Black will reclaim the pawn on e5 while enjoying the open e-file. }
8... exd4 { Ahead quite a few tempi, Black was glad to open the centre up. } 9.
Bxd4 Re8
{ With the newly half-opened e-file, Black can better accentuate the differences between the castled and uncastled Kings. }
10. Bd3 d5
{ Trying to open up the centre further. White cannot save the e-pawn. } 11. e5
Ng4 12. O-O Ngxe5 { The rest is a matter of technique. } 13. Re1 c5 14. Bxe5
Nxe5 15. Ra2 Nxd3 16. cxd3 Bf5 17. Nf1 Rxe1 18. Qxe1 Bxd3 19. Ng3 c4 20. bxc4
dxc4 21. h3 c3 22. Qc1 Rc8 23. Ne1 c2 24. Nf1 Bxf1 25. Kxf1 Bh6 26. Qxc2 Rxc2
27. Rxc2 Qd1 28. g3 Bd2 29. Rxd2 Qxd2 *

