[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Opening the Position"]
[Black "Game #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game between Ljubomir Ljubojevic playing White and Lubomir Kavalek playing Black. }
1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ Although this particular opening and variation is not wildly popular at the highest level, Black should bear in mind here that White hasn't violated any opening principles yet - The quality of his development and centre control is decent thus far. Hence, in this game, Black correctly concentrated on his own development instead of trying to 'punish' White. In fact, if Black had played too ambitiously, it could backfire. Let's suppose Black mistakenly thought that he was better here and ought to play more aggressively with 3...f5 }
3... Nf6
{ 3...f5?  Now White is the one who is better because the cons of 3...f5 outweigh the pros - Black gets a slightly better centre but is now one tempo slow and has several weaknesses around his King.  4.d4!  Now White is punishing Black by opening up the centre! This is only possible because Black played the weak 3...f5. With Black's e-pawn gone, the remaining f5 pawn will look rather silly on its own.  4...exd4  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd2  Nf6  7.Nc3  g6  8.g3  Bg7  9.Bg2  O-O  10.Nh3  Be6  11.Nf4  Bf7  12.h4  Securing the White Knight on f4 and keeping Black constantly worried about h5. With White's extra tempo and Black's extra weaknesses, White will have a pleasant game here onward. }
4. Nc3
{ 4.d4  White cannot try to open the position in the same way as if Black were to play 3...f5.  4...exd4  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd2  Be6  7.Nc3  d5  Opening up the centre to liberate the dark-squared Bishop and prevent White from gaining a monopoly on the d-file.  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Qxd5  Bxd5  11.O-O-O  O-O-O  Black is slightly ahead in development and can play ...f6 to blunt White's dark-squared Bishop. }
4... g6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3+ Be6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Ng5
{ Understandably, Black goes after e6 but this requires one move too many. }
9... O-O
{ White is effectively forced to justify Ng5 by capturing on e6 at the cost of several tempi. }
10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. g3
{ White tries to bail out of the premature foray on e6 by ignoring the pawn on e6 but it is too little, too late.   11.Qxe6+  Kh8  Black is two or three moves ahead in development and the open position makes the defence difficult for White. For example, White can already easily go wrong with  12.e3??  Nd4  Threatening the e6 Queen and the c2 fork.  13.exd4  If the Knight is taken, Black has this pin  13...Re8 }
11... d5 { Opening the centre while the h1-a8 diagonal is unguarded. } 12.
Qxe6+ { The next few moves are more or less forced. } 12... Kh8 13. Nxd5 Nxd5
14. Bxg7+ Kxg7 15. cxd5 Re8 16. Qg4 Qxd5 17. f3
{ The dust has settled, and Black can boast a huge development lead in an open position for just one pawn. With Black's Rook opposite White's uncastled King, the rest is a matter of decent attacking and tactical skills. }
17... Ne5
{ Attacking the g4 Queen and the f3 pawn, since the e2 pawn is pinned. } 18.
Rd1 Nxf3+
{ Showing why control over the e-file is so important! White will lose an exchange and get mated shortly. }
19. Kf2 Qxd1 20. exf3 Qd2+ 21. Kg1 Re1 22. Qc4 Rae8
{ Out of moves, White resigned here   22...Rae8  23.Qxc7+  Kh8  24.Qc4  Otherwise, Black has ...Rxf1+, forcing White's King to recapture, followed by Re1#  24...Rc1  25.Qb5  Re2  Now that White's Queen no longer has Qc8+, Black can safely lift his remaining Rook. Rg2# cannot be stopped now.  Conclusion: Although White's initial moves were not the most theoretical, no principles were violated and Black did not have the right to punish White. It was only when White spent too many moves going after e6 that Black had the upper hand. From there, Black's priority was to go after White's uncastled King by opening up the centre with ...d5! }
*

