{ White's uncastled King and poor development is a recipe for disaster. How can Black start the attack ? }
18... Nxf3+
{ Showing why control over the e-file is so important ! White will lose an exchange and get mated shortly. }
19. Kf2 Qxd1 { The a8 Rook will join the party soon enough. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Opening the Position"]
[Black "Game #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ For our final game in the chapter, we will analyse a casual online blitz game between two players rated above 2300. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 { We have a French Defence on board. } 3. Nc3 Nc6
{ This move blocks the c-pawn. Generally, in the French, Black wants the c-pawn to participate in the attack. With that said, Black is developing a piece to the centre and is not violating any basic opening principle. Overall, White should have the advantage after this move, but they should not expect to immediately punish Black. }
4. Nf3 { Calmly developing. } 4... Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Bd3 Bb4 7. O-O
{ Gambiting a full pawn for a bigger lead in development.   7.Bd2  Bd2 is a simpler move that consolidates White's advantage, reminding Black that they will never have good pressure on d4 without the ...c5 pawn break.  7...Nxd2  8.Qxd2 }
7... Nxc3 { Black bites. } 8. bxc3 Bxc3 9. Rb1 Bb4
{ Right now, not only is Black unable to play ...c5, they have spent three moves on the dark-squared Bishop to get it to b4 @@StartBracket@@f8-b4-c3-b4@@EndBracket@@ and another three moves on the now deceased Kingside Knight @@StartBracket@@g8-f6-e4-c3@@EndBracket@@. As a result, White has a substantial lead in development and ought to open the position. }
10. c4
{ Opening the centre.   10.Bb5?!  Is just a cheap trick on b4 that wastes a move - The Bishop was perfect on d3 and Black will be happy to retreat his Bishop to the safer e7 square.  10...Be7 }
10... dxc4
{ 10...O-O ??  Runs into the famous Greek Gift.  11.Bxh7+  Kxh7  12.Ng5+  Kg6   12...Kg8  13.Qh5+-  13.h4  Threatening h5+ and Qd3+. }
11. Bxc4
{ The pawn trade is complete. Throughout the remainder of this game, I will highlight several points that reveal the importance of this single pawn trade. }
11... O-O
{ We reach a critical point here - White has maintained their superior piece activity, but Black is ready to catch up with Be7, b6 and Bb7. How should White organise their pieces and capitalise on this fleeting advantage? }
12. Ng5
{ Clearing the d1-h5 diagonal for the Queen. Black has a severe shortage of defenders on the Kingside. Combine that with a strong White pawn on e5, and you've got yourself the correct long-term plan - bring the forces towards the Kingside and start an attack!   12.Qe2  The engine points out this move. The idea is Qe4-Qg4 and White has a formidable attack with moves like Bd3, Ng5 and Bg5/Bh6. Of course, 12. Qc2 and 12. Qd3 are also good since they all likewise bring the Queen to g4 via e4. }
12... Be7
{ 12...h6  13.Ne4  And White still has a promising attack. They can defend the d4 pawn with  Be3 before striking with moves like Qg4. As a bonus, Black must now constantly watch out for Bxh6 and Nf6+. Notice how the c4-d5 pawn trade on move 10 gives White enough space to employ this key manoeuvre. }
13. Nxh7
{ White can easily bring enough firepower in this open position to justify the piece sacrifice. }
13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Rb3
{ Here comes the Rook! Again, the c4-d5 pawn trade on move 10 has allowed the Bishop other squares besides d3, making this Rb3-Rh3 Rook lift possible. Of course, we would much rather have the Bishop on d3 than c4, but chances are Black wouldn't have castled short if that were the case.     15.Bd3  doesn't work because of  15...f5  16.exf6  Rxf6!  where Black's King can weasel away via the f8 or f7 square. }
15... Qxd4 16. Rh3 { Threatening Qh8#. } 16... f5 17. Qh7+ Kf7 18. Be2
{ The strongest move by far, but it isn't tough to spot if you have the correct thought process. Basically, Black's King's only escape square is e8, so White must find a way to control both f7 and e8! }
18... Ke8 19. Rd1
{ Taking away the d8 escape square. Again, thanks to the c4-d5 trade, and 15...Qxd4 further opening up the centre, White's Kingside Rook can make itself useful. }
19... Qxe5 20. Bh5+ g6 21. Qxg6+ Rf7 22. Qxf7#
{ Mate.   Conclusion: When ahead in development, never underestimate the power of a single pawn trade in the centre. Your pieces and attack will be significantly more powerful. In this case, the c4-d5 pawn trade allowed White to use the e4 square to attack and get the Bishop off the third rank, allowing the Rb3-Rh3 Rook lift. }
*

