[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Playing Patiently"]
[Black "Chapter Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ A common mistake many players make when attempting to punish poor openings is acting too hastily. For example, they might go for an attack or open the position when they have yet to complete their development. While this is not always the wrong strategy, striking after the whole army is ready is often more impactful.  Therefore, this chapter will be all about patience – Completing your development and maximising your piece activity before taking positive action. As with the rest of this course, the emphasis will be largely on the opening phase and its transition to the middlegame. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Playing Patiently"]
[Black "Game #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ The first game of the chapter is between GM Eugenio Torre playing White and IM Cornelis van Wijgerden playing Black. }
1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Be2 Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Re1 Qc7 8. e5
{ Torre opened up the position not only to give his dark-squared Bishop the f4 square, but also to win the e5 square for his Knight. }
8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nbd7 10. Bf4 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Qb6
{ Has either side benefitted from this series of trades on e5? Let's use the principle of reciprocating waste to find out:   White has spent 2 moves on his e-pawn @@StartBracket@@e2-e4-e5@@EndBracket@@, 2 moves on his Kingside Knight @@StartBracket@@g1-f3-e5@@EndBracket@@, and 2 moves dark-squared Bishop @@StartBracket@@c1-f4-e5@@EndBracket@@   Black has spent 2 moves on the d-pawn @@StartBracket@@d7-d6-e5@@EndBracket@@, 2 moves on the Queenside Knight @@StartBracket@@b8-d7-e5@@EndBracket@@, and 2 moves on the Queen @@StartBracket@@d8-c7-b6@@EndBracket@@.   Overall, both sides have 'wasted' 3 moves each and only White's e5 Bishop and Black's b6 Queen remain alive and developed at the end of the day. Therefore, everything cancels out and neither side has improved their lead in development from all the bloodshed on e5. However, it remains that White is slightly better thanks to his space advantage and INITIAL lead in development from when Black played the non-developing c7-c6 move. }
12. Na4 { Attacking the Queen while defending b2. } 12... Qd8
{ Black un-develops the Queen, but also reminds White that the Knight on a4 will need another move to return to civilisation. }
13. Bf3 Nd7
{ This move hinders Black's development a little bit, but it is hard to fault the Dutch IM. The point of this move is to force the trade of White's strong dark-squared Bishop. }
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. c4 e6 16. Nc3 Nf6
{ The Knight returns to its favourite square. } 17. Qd2 Bd7
{ Let's pause and assess this position. Besides the space advantage, White is clearly better not just because of his lead in development, but also because he can improve his pieces easily and freely. To maintain a monopoly on such free and easy maneuverability, White should NOT open the position. He should, be patient and focus on his own piece activity, leaving Black stuck with a set of bad pieces. }
18. Rad1
{ White is not in a rush! Black cannot do anything. For the remainder of the game, you can see how Torre enjoyed his superior maneuverability and avoided the opening the position with d5 until he was ready for it.   18.d5?  d5 throws the advantage. This is a situation where White is ahead in development but should not open the position yet.  18...exd5  19.cxd5  cxd5  Black will really appreciate this pawn trade.  20.Nxd5  Bc6  Immediately making use of the newly vacant c6 square. Now that both White and Black pieces share easy access to the d5 square, everything will trade down to an equal endgame.  21.Rad1  Nxd5  22.Bxd5  Bxd5  23.Qxd5  Qxd5  24.Rxd5= }
18... Rc8 19. Re5 { Controlling c5 and d5 further. } 19... b6 20. h4 h5 21. g3
{ Reinforcing h4 and f4. When your opponent has no moves, you have the luxury of playing these kind of patient, stabilising moves. }
21... Qe7 22. Ne2
{ Improving the Knight by brining it to f4. Additionally, White's Queen can now make use of c3 to land on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
22... Rh8 23. Nf4 Qd6 24. Qc3 Rce8 25. Rg5
{ Notice that Black's lack of space prevents him from making moves as productively as White. }
25... Rh6 26. d5
{ Now that White is 100% ready to open the position, he goes for it. } 26...
cxd5 27. Nxd5
{ This keeps the d-file open and prevents Black from shutting it down.   27.cxd5??  e5  Black closes the d-file and the a1-h8 diagonal. }
27... exd5
{ 27...e5  27...e5 doesn't work here because the d-file is open  28.Nxf6  Qxf6  29.Rxd7  And White is up a piece }
28. Rgxd5 Qc6 29. Rxd7 { The threats are Bxc6, Rd6, or simply taking on a7. }
29... Re1+
{ One final trick. White can't take the Rook with either piece because both the f3 Bishop and d7 Rook need defence. }
30. Kg2
{ With the threats of Rd6, Bxc6, and Qxe1 here, Black resigned.   Conclusion: Superior pawn placement can give you a space advantage which cramps your opponent and offers you superior maneuverability. Since your advantage stems from your pawns, you should NOT be in a hurry to open the position by trading pawns. Instead, really take your time to bring your pieces to exactly where you want them, knowing full well your opponent cannot spend their moves productively in their constricted state. }
