[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Playing Patiently"]
[Black "Game #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game played in 2005 between young Magnus Carlsen  (White)  and Atle Gronn  (Black)  . }
1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 Qb6
{ It is not clear if the Black Queen will be incredibly useful on b6. d4 is sufficiently defended and b2 is easy to defend. }
7. Qc2 Ne4 8. e3
{ Even back when Carlsen was rated only 2528, he knew what was good for him. He recognises his lead in development and focuses on completing it.   8.Nxe4  This might have been what Black had in mind when he played 6...Qb6  8...dxe4  9.Qxe4  Qxb2  10.Rb1  Qxa2  Black is up a pawn. And while White's lead in development might be scary, Black will be ready to castle sooner than White. }
8... Bb4 9. Bd3
{ When in doubt, simply develop the piece whose optimal square is most apparent. In this case, it is clear that White's light-squared Bishop belongs on d3 rather than any other square. However, it is not clear whether the a1 Rook belongs on b1, c1, or d1 for the time being. Hence, we delay its development. }
9... Qa5 10. O-O
{ Sticking to the agenda! Carlsen continued to focus on development and ignored the threat on c3. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3
{ Black has won a pawn, but it cost him one move too many. Now, where does the a1 Rook belong? }
12. Rab1
{ On the already half-open b-file, where it keeps the c8 Bishop stuck at home !   12.Rac1?!  Gaining a tempo on the c3 Bishop is not necessary. After all, Black's dark-squared Bishop wants to retreat to b4 anyway - it has no where else to go.  12...Bb4  Additionally, the Rook does not have great prospects on the c-file.  13.cxd5  exd5  White has no meaningful pressure on the c-file. }
12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 Bb4
{ White's position is good, but not yet maximised. So, now is not the time to randomly open the position and go crazy with an attack. Instead, we must first understand the nature of our advantage.   Essentially, Black has less space and is several tempi behind. As a result, his Queenside pieces cannot develop easily. Hence, Black's King will either stay in the centre or castle short. Either way, f7 will be a great target. On top of that... :  1. The f7 pawn cannot move without dramatically weakening the light squares.  2. Black has great difficulty defending f7 with minor  (low-valued)  pieces.  3. Since the f7 pawn can't really move, we can pile up on it using the e5 outpost for our Knight.  4. The e6 pawn serves as an anchor for us to open the f-file.  So, our key pawn break is f5! In contrast, opening the position with an eventual d5 is no good because... :  1.  The e-file is not completely under our control yet.  2. Black can simply castle short and will be perfectly fine.  3. Black gets to get rid of their e6 and c6 pawns to free their light-squared Bishop and Knight respectively. }
14. Ne5
{ Centralising the Knight while liberating the f-pawn and by extension, the f1 Rook. }
14... Bd6 15. f4 Qc7
{ 15...O-O  16.f5!  f7 remains a core weakness. Hence, we are eager to open both the f-file and the a2-g8 diagonal.  16...exf5  17.Nxf7  Rxf7  18.Rxb7!  Pressuring f7 from both the seventh rank and the f-file! Black's c8 Bishop is overloaded.  18...Bxb7  19.Rxf5  Even though White has 4 pieces to Black's 6, the difference in activity more than compensates. }
16. Qe4
{ Centralising the Queen and setting up a potential battery with Bd3 if Black castles short. }
16... b6 17. Nxf7 { Going after the 2 main targets, f7 and e6. } 17... Qxf7 18.
f5 Qh5 19. Bxe6 Nd7 20. f6 { Threatening Bg4+ to win Black's Queen. } 20...
Nxf6 21. Rxf6 Qxh4 22. Qxc6+ { Ignoring the Black Queen and going for mate. }
22... Ke7 23. Rf7+ Kxe6 24. Qc4#
{ Conclusion: Once White had a lead in development, he couldn't automatically win by using any old pawn break. Instead, he had to carefully identify a target that would remain relevant for several moves to come, and that target was f7. Subsequently, by recognising that there was not a lot Black could do to defend f7, White took his time with Ne5, Qe4, f4-f5, etc. }
