[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Playing Patiently"]
[Black "Game #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ Our final game of the chapter will be Anatoly Karpov vs Jan Timman. } 1. e4
d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nge2 e5 7. O-O Na6
{ Intending an eventual ...Nc5 to attack e4. } 8. Re1 c6
{ While Black has yet to make any serious mistake, White has the more comfortable game since his forces are more centralised. This can be seen by simply comparing both sides' Knights and central pawns. So, how should Karpov maintain his edge? }
9. h3
{ White has the luxury of time to control more space on the Kingside. And concretely speaking, White has secured the e3 square for his dark-squared Bishop since ...Ng4 is no longer a concern.   9.dxe5?  Opening the position does not work here. First of all, White is not significantly more active than Black to the extent that opening the position in any old way would cut it. Furthermore, this move effectively trades White's central d4 pawn for Black's less central d6 pawn. This will liberate Black's pieces with moves like ...Nc5 now made possible.  9...dxe5  10.Qxd8  Rxd8  11.a3  A necessary move to prevent ...Nb4  11...Nc5  Black's Knight has found a nice home on c5. If White ever kicks it with b2-b4, then the c4 square will become a weak outpost for Black's Knight.  12.b4  Ne6  White has to worry about the Nf6-d7-b6-c4 maneuver. }
9... Re8 { Black's long-term plan is clear - go after the e4 pawn. } 10. Bg5
{ Pinning the f6 Knight, which greatly disrupts Black's plan of pressuring e4. There are two ways to rid the Bishop. The first is Na6-c7-e6, which is rather time-consuming given that the Queenside Knight is poised for the c5 square already. The second way is ... }
10... h6
{ This is exactly what Karpov wanted. After the Bishop retreats to e3, Qd2 will come with tempo, putting White one tempo ahead than if he were to go Bc1-e3 and Qd2 earlier. }
11. Be3 Qc7 12. Qd2
{ Momentarily interrupting Black's development - Black must defend h6. } 12...
Kh7 13. Rad1 Bd7
{ White's initial space advantage has translated to better piece activity. Are we ready to strike by opening the position? }
14. g4
{ Thanks to White's space advantage, his preparatory moves are more productive than Black's. Hence, Karpov calmly goes with g2-g4 and Ne2-g3 before proceeding with the committal f2-f4 pawn break.   14.f4  While playing f4 immediately is by no means, a mistake, there are some risks involved. For example, if Black played similar moves as he did in the game...  14...Rad8  15.g4  b5  16.a3  b4  17.axb4  Nxb4  Here White would love to organise their pieces by playing Ne2-g3 and Nc3-e2, bringing more forces to the Kingside. Additionally, this plan would clear the way for c2-c3, reinforcing the centre and kicking Black's Knight. However, White is one move slow.  18.Ng3?!  Nxg4!  Striking at d4 just before White is able to reinforce it with Nc3-e2  19.hxg4  exd4  20.Bxd4  Bxd4+  21.Qxd4  Nxc2  White's advantage is no longer obvious. }
14... Rad8 15. Ng3 { Again, Karpov maximises his position before going f2-f4. }
15... Bc8
{ 15...b5  Let's see how this move works when White has yet to waste a move on f4.  16.a3  b4  17.axb4  Nxb4  18.Nce2!  White has saved a tempo by not committing to f4 yet. As a result, he now has time to bring the Knights to the kingside and reinforce the centre!  18...exd4  19.Bxd4  c5  20.Be3  Besides the extra tempo, avoiding the f4 move allows White the additional options of Bf4 and g4-g5. }
16. f4
{ The time is ripe - White is out of productive moves.   16.Rf1?!  One might think that this Rook move might be useful before playing f4. The problem is that the Rook has greater responsibility controlling the e-file. This allows Black good counterplay in the centre.  16...d5!  Blowing open the centre while White's Rook is inactive and has yet to play f4.  17.dxe5  Nxe4  18.Ncxe4  dxe4  19.Qc1  Qxe5  20.Nxe4  White's space and developmental advantage is gone. }
16... b5 17. a3
{ Patient play to take away the opponent's counterplay. The idea is that Black can only push his b-pawn on the condition he is willing to isolate his a-pawn and put his Knight on b4. This will mean the Knight is a little far from its favourite c5 square, where it can attack e4.   17.Nce2  exd4  18.Nxd4  Nc5 }
17... b4 18. axb4 Nxb4 19. Nce2 exd4 20. Nxd4
{ If Black's Knight had been on a6 rather than b4, White would have to deal with the annoying ...Nc5 move now. }
20... a5 21. c3 Na6 22. Qc2
{ Black wants to play ...Nc5 to attack e4. Ideally, White wants to kick it with b2-b4 as soon as that happens, without dropping the e4 pawn. Hence, Karpov first overprotects e4 with 22.Qc2. }
22... Bd7
{ We can only guess that Black's idea is ...c5 followed by ...Bc6. It remains that White has a strong static advantage, especially on the Kingside, and Black must constantly worry about both the f5 and g5 pawn breaks.   22...Nc5  23.b4 }
23. Nf3
{ Probably the most productive, non-committal move here. White allows the e3 Bishop to control c5 while supporting both the e5 and g5 pawn breaks. This will certainly offer White a strong psychological advantage as Black is kept paranoid throughout the game. }
23... Re7 24. Bf2
{ The final preparatory move. White opens the e-file to offer more support to his only weakness, the e4 pawn. }
24... Be8
{ With weaknesses on both sides of the board, Black cracks here. How can White target all of Black's weaknesses at once? }
25. Qd3
{ Attacking the a6 Knight while pressuring and pinning the d6 pawn. The e5 pawn break is looking stronger than ever. }
25... Qb7
{ The Knight is defended, but now the a-pawn loses its much needed support. }
26. Ra1 Nc7 27. Rxa5
{ White snatches a pawn while retaining all the positional advantages. For Karpov, the rest is a matter of elementary technique. }
27... Rdd7 28. b4 Ne6 29. Be3 c5 30. f5 { Gaining more space on the Kingside. }
30... Nd8 31. b5 Kh8 32. Bf2 Qc7 33. Ra4 Qb8 34. c4 Ra7
{ Black challenges the a-file, but now the d-file loses its support. This means White can trade Rooks and go for the e5 pawn break. }
35. Rxa7 Rxa7 36. e5 dxe5 37. Nxe5 Ra2 38. Bxc5
{ Up two pawns in a strategically dominant position, the game ended 1-0 here.   Conclusion: Early in the game, Black allowed White to put pawns in the centre in hopes that they could become targets. In response, Karpov was remarkably forbearing - Securing e4 and improving his pieces to the maximum before opening the position with f4. Another reason to play patiently was that Black lacked space and could not spend the time improving his pieces as much as White did. }
