[FEN "r3r3/ppqb1pbk/n1pp1npp/4p3/3PP3/2N1B1PP/PPPQNPB1/3RR1K1 w - - 6 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White's initial space advantage has translated to better piece activity. Are we ready to strike by opening the position? }
14. g4
{ Thanks to White's space advantage, his preparatory moves are more productive than Black's. Hence, Karpov calmly goes with g2-g4 and Ne2-g3 before proceeding with the committal f2-f4 pawn break.   14.f4  While playing f4 immediately is by no means, a mistake, there are some risks involved. For example, if Black played similar moves as he did in the game...  14...Rad8  15.g4  b5  16.a3  b4  17.axb4  Nxb4  Here White would love to organise their pieces by playing Ne2-g3 and Nc3-e2, bringing more forces to the Kingside. Additionally, this plan would clear the way for c2-c3, reinforcing the centre and kicking Black's Knight. However, White is one move slow.  18.Ng3?!  Nxg4!  Striking at d4 just before White is able to reinforce it with Nc3-e2  19.hxg4  exd4  20.Bxd4  Bxd4+  21.Qxd4  Nxc2  White's advantage is no longer obvious. }
14... Rad8 15. Ng3 { Again, Karpov maximises his position before going f2-f4. }
15... Bc8
{ 15...b5  Let's see how this move works when White has yet to waste a move on f4.  16.a3  b4  17.axb4  Nxb4  18.Nce2!  White has saved a tempo by not committing to f4 yet. As a result, he now has time to bring the Knights to the kingside and reinforce the centre!  18...exd4  19.Bxd4  c5  20.Be3  Besides the extra tempo, avoiding the f4 move allows White the additional options of Bf4 and g4-g5. }
16. f4
{ The time is ripe - White is out of productive moves.   16.Rf1?!  One might think that this Rook move might be useful before playing f4. The problem is that the Rook has greater responsibility controlling the e-file. This allows Black good counterplay in the centre.  16...d5!  Blowing open the centre while White's Rook is inactive and has yet to play f4.  17.dxe5  Nxe4  18.Ncxe4  dxe4  19.Qc1  Qxe5  20.Nxe4  White's space and developmental advantage is gone. }
