[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Slowing the Enemy"]
[Black "Chapter Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ So far, we have learnt to identify dubious play and punish it through three methods:  1.	Pressuring a specific target  2.	Opening the position to expose a target  3.	First getting all your pieces ready before taking action  In this chapter, we will be looking at the final strategy - how to slow down your opponent’s development. This can be done through various means including pinning enemy pieces to make their development congested, pressuring weak spots to keep its defenders passive, or even just preventing castling. We’ll explore all of this in the following games. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Slowing the Enemy"]
[Black "Game #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ The first one is a really short game between Alex Yermolinsky  (White)  and Emory A Tate  (Black) }
1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 exd5 4. Nxd5 Ne7
{ Blocking the dark-squared Bishop. How did Yermolinsky keep the Knight on this square? }
5. Bg5
{ White is already better. It is difficult for Black to untangle his Kingside pieces. }
5... h6
{ 5...f6  As mentioned in the very first chapter, moving the f-pawn is often a huge concession because it weakens the a2-g8 diagonal and the h5-e8 diagonal.  6.Bf4  Nxd5  7.Qxd5  White's Queen cannot be easily displaced. This means White will have comfortable pressure on the backward d-pawn while preventing Black from castling kingside. }
6. Bh4
{ 6.Bf6!!  The engine points out that this is not just a cheap attempt to get a quick mate, but in fact, a strong strategical move that prevents both the e7 Knight and the g-pawn from moving for quite a while. Alternatively, White can just take on e7 next move to force Black to take a ghastly pawn structure.  6...d6  7.Nxe7   7.e4  White can also just continue with normal development. Black is still tied up on the kingside and can't take the Bishop because of smothered mate.  gxf6   7...Bxe7  Loses the g7 pawn  8.Bxg7  8.Nxc8  Qxc8  Black's pawn structure allows White to use the f4 and d5 square for the Knight. }
6... Qa5+
{ Unpins the Knight with check   6...g5??  Don't hang mate in 1!  7.Nf6 } 7. c3
Nf5
{ 7...Nxd5  After trading Knights, Black will be doing just fine.  8.Qxd5  Nc6 }
8. Qa4
{ The c7 square is a huge tactical target - Nc7 would be mate if not for the Black Queen! }
8... Qxa4 { 8...Nc6  9.Qxa5  Nxa5  10.Nc7 } 9. Nc7#
{ Conclusion: Black played 4...Ne7 which congested his own development. Hence, White's correctly kept the Knight on that square by pinning it. After Black tried to kick the Bishop with 5...h6, White's best reply was 6.Bf6!! maintaining the pin on the Knight and attacking g7, giving Black a tough time developing their Kingside. }
