[SetUp "1"]

{ Black appears to have cleverly untangled their pieces, but at what cost ? }
8. Qa4
{ The dark squares are now left unattended and c7 is a huge tactical target - Nc7 would be mate if not for the Black Queen ! }
8... Nc6 { 8...Qxa4  9.Nc7 } 9. Qxa5 Nxa5 10. Nc7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Slowing the Enemy"]
[Black "Game #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Next up we have Paul Morphy vs Thomas Inglis Hampton. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit. This move effectively forces the Black Bishop to b4 so that White can play c3 with tempo }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 6. O-O d6 7. d4
{ White has given up the b-pawn for two tempi, which he spent on c3 and d4. }
7... exd4
{ Black is trading his central e5 pawn for White's lousy c3 pawn without any compensation.   7...Bb6  Without the inclusion of ...exd4 and cxd4, Black gets a say in the centre and perhaps the best White can do is trade Queens to win back the gambited pawn.  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8+  Nxd8  Better to take with the Knight and lose e5 than to take with the King and lose f7.   9...Kxd8?  10.Bxf7±  e5 remains a target  10.Nxe5  Nf6  Black will castle and go ...Re8 }
8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 Nf6
{ White has a model development set up but Black is about to castle. How did Morphy stop it? }
10. e5
{ Opening the position! The Knight has nowhere to run. Black is obliged to play ...dxe5. }
10... dxe5
{ 10...Ng4  11.h3  Nh6  12.Bg5!  A strong zwischenzug before taking on h6! Black must either play Qd7 or Ne7, and both moves will slow his development.  12...Qd7  Blocking the light-squared Bishop  13.Bxh6  Damaging the kingside pawn structure so Black can't castle short safely.  13...gxh6  14.Nd5!  Going after the f6 target. }
11. Ba3 { Stopping Black from castling - the point of 10. e5! } 11... Bg4 12.
Qb3
{ Going after the f7 target a getting the Queen off the d-file so that White can take on e5 without allowing a Queen trade. }
12... Bh5 13. dxe5 Ng4 14. Rad1
{ Completing development while forcing Black's Queen to a bad square. } 14...
Qc8 15. e6
{ It is time to open the position! If the e6 pawn is taken, White has a mating attack. Otherwise, White simply has yet another powerful attacker - the e6 pawn! }
15... f6 { 15...fxe6  16.Bxe6  Qb8  17.Bd7+  Kd8  18.Bxc6+  Kc8  19.Qe6 } 16.
Qb5
{ With Black so severely underdeveloped, White can simply pick a target, then add pressure to it. In this case, the victim is the c6 Knight. White pins it while attacking the h5 Bishop. The next step is to add one more attacker to c6. }
16... Bg6 17. Bd5
{ Out of moves, Black resigned here.   Conclusion: Black's key mistake was 7...exd4 because it unnecessarily gave up the centre. Subsequently, just before Black could castle, White opened the position with 10.e5 and then 11.Ba3 to stop Black from castling. Once Black's King was stuck in the centre, the rest was a matter of identifying targets  (such as f7, the e-file, and c6)  and going after them. }
