[Black "Game #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ Finally, we conclude the chapter with a game from the 2019 World Rapid Championship between Magnus Carlsen and Azamat Utegaliyev. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
{ The Black Queen is moving a second time, but so has White's e-pawn. } 4. d4
c6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Ne5
{ Making it difficult for Black to develop the light-squared Bishop by controlling the g4 square. White can afford to move the knight twice because Black had already played the slow but necessary ...c6 move. }
6... Nbd7
{ 6...Bf5  Trying to get the light-squared Bishop active.  7.g4  Bg6  8.f4  Threatening f5.  8...e6  9.Qe2  Pinning e-pawn and renewing the threat of f4-f5.  9...Be7  10.h4  White is doing very well with his huge kingside space advantage. }
7. Nc4 Qc7 8. a4
{ Stopping b5!   8.Bd3?  If White had played any innocuous move, Black would play ...b5 to kick the c4 Knight followed by the ...e5 pawn break.  8...b5  9.Nd2  e5  Black finally regains equality in centre control and has both Bishops liberated.   Also, White can afford this slow move because Black has already blocked his own Bishop with ...Nbd7. If the d7 Knight were on g6 instead  (See here --> @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppq1pppp/2p2nn1/8/P1NP4/2N5/1PP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq a3 0 8@@EndFEN@@)  , Black would be ahead in development and White would be worse. }
8... a5
{ 8...e5??  Doesn't work because White has sufficient control over the e5 square.  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Qe2  Attacking and pinning the e5 Knight. Also, White has f4 to pressure the pinned Knight if necessary. }
9. Qf3 { Preparing Bf4 to challenge Black's Queen. } 9... Nb6 10. Bf4
{ Developing with tempo. Now Black must un-develop the Queen. } 10... Qd8 11.
Be5
{ A multi-purpose move! It defends d4 and prevents Black from fianchettoing his dark-squared Bishop. }
11... Nbd5
{ 11...g6  12.Nd6+!!  Exploiting all the dark squares!  12...exd6   12...Kd7  13.Nxf7  With a fork  13.Bxf6  With a fork }
12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. c3
{ Reinforcing the centre. Again, notice how the e5 Bishop's pressure on g7 makes it difficult for Black to get his kingside active. }
13... Nf6 14. Bd3 Be6 15. O-O { Effectively completing development. } 15...
Bxc4 16. Bxc4 e6
{ The dark-squared Bishop is trying to get out. What should you do? } 17. Qg3
{ Exactly! Keep the f8 Bishop at home by renewing the pressure on g7. } 17...
g6
{ Trying to bring the Bishop to g7. White has a huge lead in development here, and it is time to take action. How do you expose Black's uncastled King position? }
18. f4
{ This move stops the Bishop from going to g7 by threatening f4-f5!  The engine points out a brilliant move which Carlsen missed.   18.d5!!  This forces to open the position one way or another.  18...cxd5  Exposes the a4-e8 diagonal.   18...exd5  Exposes the e-file.  19.Rfe1  There are no good moves here.  19...Be7  20.Bxf6  Making use of the pin.   18...Bg7  If Black doesn't do anything about d5, White will take on e6.  19.dxe6  19.Bb5+  Ke7  20.c4  Further opening up the position! Black's King will not survive in the middle. }
18... Bg7
{ 18...Be7  Without an unprotected Bishop on g7, White's f5 move will not work.  19.f5?  gxf5 }
19. f5
{ Threatening to take on e6. The g6 pawn cannot capture because the g7 Bishop will hang. }
19... exf5
{ The e-file is finally open. This is White's one chance to take action before Black can castle. }
20. Bc7
{ Getting the Bishop off the e-file with tempo. This ensures that Re1 will come with check and Black will be unable to castle. }
20... Qc8
{ 20...Qd7  21.Rae1+  Ne4  22.Rxe4+  fxe4  23.Bxf7+  Qxf7  24.Rxf7  Kxf7  25.Qf4+  Kg8  26.Qxe4  Even though material is equal here, White is much better thanks to his better piece coordination and activity. Black's Rooks are unconnected and the g7 Bishop is biting on rock. }
21. Qd6
{ Stopping Black from castling and adding a formidable attacker to the king hunt. }
21... Ne4 22. Rae1 Qd7 23. Rxe4+ fxe4 24. Bxf7+ Qxf7 25. Rxf7 Kxf7 26. Qd7+
{ Black resigned here because mate will follow shortly.   26.Qd7+  Kf6  27.Be5+   26.Qd7+  Kf8  27.Bd6+  Kg8  28.Qe6   26.Qd7+  Kg8  27.Qe6+  Kf8  28.Bd6    Conclusion: White was slightly better by move 10. In order to compound this advantage, White had to prevent Black from organising his Kingside. Specifically, White prevented Black's f8 Bishop from developing by continually pressuring g7 and other dark squares. Once Black's development was slowed down sufficiently, White promptly opened the position with f4-f5 and attacked Black's uncastled King. }
