{ This was one of my casual rapid games in a local club against a player rated about 1900 online. }
1. e4 Nc6 2. Bc4 e5 3. Qf3
{ The mate on f7 can be easily defended. All that will remain is White's Kingside Knight deprived of its favourite f3 square and a potential ...Nd4 move looming. }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. a3 { Wasting even more time. } 5... O-O 6. Qd1
{ White has officially wasted 3 tempi - Two moves on the Queen and one on the a-pawn. Additionally, Black is well-developed and hence ready to open the position. }
6... d5
{ Preparing to develop the light-squared Bishop while opening the position.   6...d6?  These are the sort of slow, non-combative moves that allow the opponent to catch up easily.  7.Nf3  Bg4  8.h3  Bh5  9.O-O  Nd4  10.Nbd2  While Black is better, he does not have the necessary resources for a decisive attack. }
7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. O-O Nd4 11. Nbd2 Nf4
{ With White's e-pawn and Black's d-pawn traded, Black has a few additional routes to White's King. For example, Nf6-d5-f4. }
12. Kh2 Qf6 13. Ne4
{ White can likewise use the extra space created by the pawn trade for his own attack. However, Black is three tempi up and is in a better position to attack. }
13... Qh6 14. Nxc5 Bxf3 15. gxf3
{ 15.Bxf4  Qxf4+  16.g3  Qf5  17.Qc1   17.Qd2  This puts the White King and Queen within forking distance.  17...Be2  The threats are ...Bxf1 and ...Nf3+  Bc6  Black has a strong light square attack incoming! }
15... Qxh3+ 16. Kg1 Qg2# *

