[Black "Game #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is yet another one from Daniel Naroditsky's speedrun series. Here, the American Grandmaster has the Black pieces against GontseSeisoAndries1  (1572)  . }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Bg5 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. f4
{ Black has gotten his pieces out quickly and castled while White has spent 4 of their first 6 moves on pawns. However, those 4 pawns control a great portion of the centre. This leads to a delicate situation where White is objectively fine, but must keep his centre together at all costs. If Black can trade some central pawns, all that will remain is White's undeveloped Kingside pieces and uncastled King. }
6... c5 { A great start to tearing down White's centre. } 7. e5
{ White should NOT be trading the pawns. How can Black trade off as many central pawns as possible ?   7.d5!  White wants to keep his central pawns alive because so many moves have been invested in them. They help conceal White's underdeveloped pieces. }
7... cxd4 8. exf6
{ 8.Qxd4  Nc6  White will soon win the e-pawn and be up material. } 8... exf6
{ Black has lost a piece but White cannot save both their g5 Bishop and c3 Knight. }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Ne4 Re8
{ After the whole fiasco, Black is up one pawn. More importantly, the position is now very open and White has nothing to show for all their moves invested into their non-existent central pawns. }
11. Nf3
{ 11.Bd3  There is no use in holding on to the Knight. Black can just keep on adding attackers and White needs one move too many to get their King to safety.  11...Bf5  12.Qe2  Bxe4  13.Bxe4  Nd7  Nc5 incoming.  14.b4  d3  Both White's Queen and a1 Rook are hanging.  15.Qxd3  Bxa1 }
11... Rxe4+ 12. Be2 Qe7
{ Black maintains principled play despite having such a huge advantage! By adding an attacker to the e2 Bishop, White is unable to castle. }
13. Qd3 Re3 14. Qd2 d3 { Attacking the pinned Bishop. The game is over. } 15.
O-O dxe2 16. Rfe1 Nc6 *

