{ This is an online blitz game between two players rated above 2600 on lichess, batgemini  (White)  vs Emad3000  (Black)  . }
1. e4 c5 2. d4 Nc6 { An unfortunate premove. } 3. d5
{ White takes full control of the centre and forces Black to un-develop the Knight. }
3... Nb8
{ As with many games in this course, White is better but it isn't an auto-win. We must use the strategies and maintain principled play. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. f4
{ Now that Black's pawn is fixed on d6, it is best for White to prepare the e5 pawn break. }
5... Nf6
{ Black should not be inviting e5 unless they are sufficiently developed to chip away at White's resulting pawn centre.   5...g6  or any other productive move that doesn't allow White to play e5 with tempo would be more resilient. }
6. e5 dxe5 7. fxe5 Ng8
{ Now, White Black has wasted 4 tempi on their 2 Knights. Also, White has done a good job opening the position a little. }
8. Bb5+ { Getting the Bishop out with tempo to castle quickly. } 8... Bd7 9.
Nf3 { 9.Bxd7+?!  This will help Black catch up in development.  9...Nxd7 } 9...
Bxb5 10. Nxb5 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 g6 12. O-O Bg7
{ White has finally more or less completed their development. What's the plan? }
13. d6 { Further opening the position before Black can castle. } 13... exd6 14.
Ne4
{ White shows a very good understanding of the targets. Black's actual weaknesses are f7 and the d6 square.   14.exd6  With the idea of Re1+ is not as strong. White's pieces are much better coordinated to go after f7.  14...Nd7  15.Re1+  Kf8  After calculating a few lines, it will start to feel like White's Rook should belong on f1 instead. }
14... dxe5 15. Nd6+ Ke7 16. Qd5
{ Going straight for f7. There is no way to defend it and the rest of the game was a very precise mate. }
16... Qc7 17. Qxf7+ Kxd6 18. Rd1+ Kc6 19. Qe6+ Kb5 20. a4+ Ka5 21. Bd2# *

