8. Qb3 { We are going after f7! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Easy Exercises"]
[Black "Game #4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Here, we have a 10-minute game from lichess between two players rated about 1800, JDplaysnow vs IB2stoned2chatPLZ. }
1. e4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the Tennison Gambit, which gives up the e4 pawn and some tempi on the Knight in exchange for some tactical chances. However, as long as Black plays principled chess, White will be substantially worse out of the opening. }
2... dxe4 3. Ng5 f5
{ Neglecting development while weakening the a2-g8 and h5-e8 diagonals. Black should have either developed while defending the pawn, or returned the material for a lead in development.   3...Nf6   3...Bf5   3...Nc6  4.Nxe4  e5  White has gotten the pawn back, but is behind in development. }
4. Bc4
{ Exploiting the weakened diagonal and targeting f7. Black must either return a pawn with ...e6 or bring their Knight to the suboptimal h6 square }
4... Nh6
{ 4...e6  5.Nxe6  Bxe6  6.Bxe6  Material is equal and Black's King is pretty exposed. }
5. d3
{ If Black's King is weaker and White is ahead in development, then opening the position is certainly the way to go ! }
5... exd3 6. cxd3
{ This looks like it merely damages the pawn structure, but it, in fact, shows that White truly knows what the game is about. Since Black's main weakness is f7 and, by extension, the Black King, White would not want to bring his Bishop back from c4 to d3 or to allow a Queen trade with Qxd3.   Instead, 6.cxd3 allows White to develop the Queen to b3, adding more pressure to f7. }
6... e5 7. O-O
{ Completing development. You can already tell the e-file is about to become critical. }
7... f4
{ Trying to block the c1 Bishop to threaten the g5 Knight, but Black cannot afford to grab so much space while none of their pieces are working.   On another note, to show the relevance of allowing a potential Qb3 move with 6.cxd3, here's another reasonable way the game could have proceeded.   7...g6  8.Qb3!  Black can either allow Bf7+ and lose the right to castle, or defend f7 with an awkward Queen move.  8...Bg7   8...Qe7  exacerbates the problems along the e-file.  9.d4   8...Qd7  Blocks the c8 Bishop and weakens control over e6.  9.Be6  Qd8  10.Bf7+  9.Bf7+ }
8. Bxf4
{ White's advantage is sufficiently large! White can open up the e-file at the cost of a Bishop. }
8... exf4 9. Qh5+
{ 9.Re1+?  Move order is important! We cannot let Black's King escape to f8.  9...Be7  Vacating the f8 square.  10.Qh5+  Kf8  It is tougher for White to breakthrough now compared to what happened in the main game. }
9... g6 10. Re1+ Kd7 { 10...Be7??  11.Qxh6 } 11. Qe2
{ The target is now the e-file and specifically, the e6 square. } 11... Bb4
{ Black blundered mate, but they were losing in any case.   Even if Black had defended the mate, White could dominate the e6 square with a decisive attacking position.   11...Qe7  12.Ne6  Nc6  13.Nc3  White could get some action on the d-file by pushing the d-pawn and Nb5/Nd5 is always looming. In the meantime, it is incredibly difficult for Black to regain control over the e6 square. }
12. Qe6# *

