{ White is easily dominating. What is the cleanest way to finish the game? }
27. Qxe7
{ Creating a passed e-pawn. White will excuse the Queen and go e7-e8. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Easy Exercises"]
[Black "Game #5"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is an online 3+0 game between GM Oleksandr Bortnyk and GM Mahammad Muradli. }
1. e4 Nf6
{ This is the Alekhine's Defence. Even though it does not contest the centre with pawns, it is perfectly playable. The idea is to offer White the centre, only to target it later in the game. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ White maintains the tension to preserve his centre control. } 4... dxe5 5. c4
Nf6
{ This move is ever so slightly dubious. Black's Knight really belongs on b6 where it targets c4. On top of that, it will not block Black's dark-squared Bishop which is arriving on g7 shortly. }
6. Nxe5 c6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. Be3
{ 8.f4  This is the best move. It maintains control over the centre without ever allowing Black to trade Queens.  8...Nxe5  9.fxe5 }
8... Qa5
{ 8...Nxe5  Due to a rather specific, forcing line, Black can eliminate part of White's advantage with this move.  9.dxe5  Qxd1+  10.Rxd1  With many pieces already developed, it appears that White should be comfortably better, especially at the Grandmaster level. However, Black has the move ....  10...Ng4  Hitting e3 and e5.  11.Bd4   11.Bf4  g5  12.Bxg5  Nxe5  Black can get some activity with Rg8 or Bg7.  f6  12.exf6  exf6  White is still better, but at least Black isn't suffocated. }
9. f4 Nxe5 10. fxe5 Ne4 11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. Qd2
{ Of course, White didn't blunder anything. He pins the Knight to the a5 Queen and will regain his material easily. }
12... g6 13. bxc3 Bg7 14. O-O O-O 15. Rf3
{ Preparing to double up on the f-file -  White's main strength and Black's weakness. }
15... Be6 16. Raf1 Rad8 17. h4 { Throwing another attacker to the Kingside. }
17... b5 18. cxb5 cxb5 19. h5 Rc8 20. h6 Bh8
{ The Bishop is buried in for good. } 21. Bg5 Rc7 22. Be4 Qxa2 23. Qf4 Bd5 24.
e6
{ 24.Bxd5!  By getting rid of the e4 Bishop first, White avoids the tactical complications related to ...Bxe4.  24...Qxd5  25.e6  Qxe6  26.Qxc7  White is up a clean Rook. }
24... f6
{ 24...Bxe4  This makes things mildly troublesome for White, but White will eventually come out up a clean exchange.  25.exf7+  Qxf7  26.Qxf7+  Rxf7  27.Rxf7  Bf5  28.Rxe7  Rxe7  29.Bxe7 }
25. Bxd5 Qxd5 26. Qxc7 Qxg5 27. Qxe7
{ White's simple plan is to Queen the e-pawn. } 27... Qxh6 28. Qd7
{ There's no stopping e7-e8. } *

