{ To start us off on the intermediate exercises, we have a game between two Grandmasters, GM Walter Browne  (White)  and GM Robert Byrne  (Black)  . }
1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3 Be6 6. Bd3 g6 7. Qf3 c6 8.
Nge2 Nd7
{ So far, 5 out of 8 moves by Black are pawn moves. Moreover, the time spent on Black pieces did not bring them to fantastic squares. Black is only alive because all these pawns are concealing his underdevelopment. Hence, we must find an anchor to trade pawns. }
9. h3 { f5 is the anchor and White wants to open the position with g4. } 9...
Qb6 10. g4
{ 10.O-O-O  Castling long to defend b2 before playing g4 was also correct. }
10... Qxb2
{ This gives White activity on both wings of the board. The White King is safe in the centre because it is very closed. Furthermore, Black isn't nearly active enough to go for a King hunt.  What if Black had played   10...fxg4  11.hxg4  The h-file is now open and is both tactically and strategically exploitable.  11...Qxb2  12.Rb1  Qa3  13.Bxg6+!  Either misplacing Black's King or winning an exchange and a pawn.  13...hxg6  14.Rxh8 }
11. Rb1 Qa3 12. gxf5 { Opening the position one way or another. } 12... Bf7
{ Black tries to preserve his pawn structure. } 13. Rxb7
{ Not only winning a pawn, but also weakening Black on the light squares around the Queenside. }
13... Bb4 { Did White blunder a piece ? } 14. O-O O-O-O
{ Trapping the b7 Rook, but White now has a simple way to own the b-file.   14...Bxc3  15.Rb3  White wins his piece back easily and Black loses his good Bishop. }
15. Rxb4 Qxb4 16. Ba6+
{ Securing the b7 square so that the threat of Rb1 is meaningful.   16.Rb1  Qa5  The Bishop can't go to a6, which means the Rook can't land on b7. }
16... Kc7 17. Rb1 Qd6 18. Rb7+ Kc8 19. Rb3+ Kc7 20. Rb7+ Kc8
{ With a bit of creativity, White imagined the fastest way to bring another attacker to the game and turned it to reality. }
21. e4 { Allowing the f3 Queen access along the third rank. } 21... Nb8 22. Nb5
{ Threatening Nxd6 and Nxa7#. } 22... cxb5 23. Qc3+ { The Queen is in ! } 23...
Nc6 24. e5
{ Now White simply chases the d6 Queen away from the defence of the c6 Knight. }
24... Qc7 25. e6
{ Covering the d7 escape square. White's discovered attack carries more venom than ever. Black resigned here in view of   25.e6  Qxb7  26.Qxc6+  Kb8  27.Qxb7 }
*

