[White "8. Intermediate Exercises"]
[Black "Game #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ This one is a game played back in 1997 between Voller, Jiri  (2265)  and Moravec, Michal  (2255)  . }
1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Nf3 Nh6
{ 4...Nf6  Black should bring their Knight towards the centre. } 5. Bf4 f6 6.
Qd2 Nf7 7. Bc4
{ Black has put all of his pawns on dark squares and we must exploit the softened light squares accordingly. }
7... e6 8. h4
{ Black is severely underdeveloped and we must expose that by opening the position. Based on the structure, the easiest place to trade pawns is the Kingside and centre.   8.g4?  e5  Double attacking the e5 Bishop and g4 pawn. }
8... h6 9. O-O-O
{ We want to play g4-g5 to open the position. Hence, our King belongs on the Queenside. }
9... O-O 10. g4 Nc6
{ 10...e5?  The e6 pawn was responsible for blocking the a2-g8 diagonal. Now, the f7 Knight is pinned and h6 is hanging.  11.Bxh6  Bxh6  12.Qxh6  Black will get mated shortly. }
11. g5 { Finally, the pawns make contact. } 11... fxg5 12. hxg5 h5
{ Black, of course, tries to avoid pawn trades, but the position is far too open and riddled with weaknesses. }
13. Nh4 { Going after g6. } 13... Ne7 14. Qe2
{ Going after another strategical target, the h-file. The threat is Nxg6, then Qxh5. }
14... Ne5
{ Unleashing a discovered attack on White's f4 Bishop. This forces White to trade one of the Bishops for the Black Knight.   14...Nh8  This is the toughest defence. First of all, White must deal with his hanging f4 Bishop. Furthermore, if White ever sacrifices on g6, Black will play Nhxg6, park the King on f7, and transfer the f8 Rook to h8.  15.Be3  c6  16.Nxg6  Nhxg6  17.Qxh5  Kf7  18.Bd3  Rh8  White is probably winning here, but Black is making White work hard to justify the piece sacrifice. }
15. Bxe5
{ The best way to make the Bishop-Knight trade. The idea is to open both the d-file and the a2-g8 diagonal. }
15... dxe5 16. d5 { Indeed the d-file and a2-g8 diagonal will open. } 16... Qe8
17. dxe6 c6 18. Kb1
{ Safety first. White is in no rush and should take the time to save himself from any tricks along the c1-h6 diagonal. }
18... b5
{ 18...a6  If Black made any innocuous move, White will force a win on the light squares with ...  19.Rd7!  If the Rook is taken, exd7 will open the a2-g8 diagonal with check, winning the Black Queen. Otherwise, White will play Rxe7 followed by Nxg6.  19...b5   19...Bxd7  20.exd7+  Kh8  21.dxe8=Q  20.Rxe7  Qxe7  21.Nxg6  Qxg5  Thanks to Kb1, this capture does not come with check.  22.e7+  White is winning for so many reasons. }
19. Nxb5 { Exploiting the trappable e8 Queen. } 19... cxb5 20. Bxb5
{ The Queen has no squares. Black must give up a piece somehow. } 20... Nc6 21.
e7 { Opening the a2-g8 diagonal. } 21... Qxe7 22. Bxc6 Rb8 23. Bd5+
{ White is up two pawns and is dominating Black's King. The game concluded shortly. }
23... Rf7 24. Qc4 Bg4 25. f3 *

