{ Some of you may wonder how to punish such unprincipled play if the opponent doesn't castle. Hence, I've included this very similar game where Black played ...Qe7 instead of castling. Your move. }
10. e5 { Forcing the centre to open. } 10... dxe5 11. dxe5 f5
{ Black's toughest defence will often involve avoiding pawn trades as much as possible. }
12. Bg5
{ Highlighting Black's two main problems. They will either face a serious attack on the dark squares, or allow our Knight to reach g5 and exert permanent pressure on e6. }
12... Nxg5 13. Nxg5
{ Black will probably never be able to develop his light-squared Bishop and Queenside pieces. White's plan is Rh3-Rd3 to own the d-file. On top of that, Nd5 is a serious possibility to open the a2-g8 diagonal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
