{ Black is neither developing quickly nor controlling the centre. } 5. O-O
{ Although White has a lead development, they still don't have the forces necessary to open the position successfully. }
5... h6 6. c4 g5 { Black is wasting one move too many.. } 7. Nc3
{ White correctly aims to develop all their pieces first. } 7... Bb4 8. Bd2
Bxc3 9. Bxc3 d6 10. d5
{ Opening up the centre! Black's undeveloped pieces can no longer hide behind all the pawns. }
10... e5 11. Nxe5
{ White is so far ahead in development and centre control that they can afford to give up material to open up the position. }
11... dxe5 12. Bxe5
{ Let's consider White's gain from the Knight sacrifice. White has got two pawns, activated the dark-squared Bishop, and gave White's pieces an easy development plan. The light-squared Bishop can activate with an e5 pawn push, the f1 Rook can come to life with the f4 pawn break, and the Queen has the f3, g4, and h5 squares made available. }
12... f6
{ 12...Rh7  13.Bc3!  If Black had played 12...Rh7 or 12...Nf6, White can pull the Bishop back to prepare e5, then e6! The e-file, b1-h7 diagonal, and a1-h8 diagonal will all open up nicely. }
13. Qh5+ { Slowing the enemy! Black's King must lose the right to castle. }
13... Kf8 14. Bc3 Nd7
{ Developing and discouraging White from opening the position with e5. So White finds another way to open lines. }
15. f4 Kg7 16. fxg5 hxg5 17. Qxg5+
{ Making use of the pin from the c3 Bishop. } 17... Kf8 18. e5
{ Adding more pressure to the weak f6 pawn. } 18... Nc5 19. exf6
{ The threat is Qg7+ followed by Bg6#. } 19... Qd7 { Defending g7. } 20. Qg7+
{ Qg7 anyway! } 20... Qxg7 21. fxg7+
{ Black resigned as White will take the Rook, make a new Queen, and mate Black shortly. }
*

