[Black "Game #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nd7
{ This is the Hanham variation of the Philidor Defence. It isn't very popular for good reason - both the d6 pawn and d7 Knight are blocking their own Bishops. This gives White a slight to moderate advantage and they should look to continue developing swiftly. }
4. Bc4 h6 { Too many slow moves. This allows a neat tactic } 5. dxe5 dxe5 6.
Bxf7+ Kxf7 7. Nxe5+ { The d7 Knight is pinned to the d8 Queen } 7... Kf6
{ As White, it's important to remember not to get too comfortable here. Black's King may be quite exposed, but White is still down some material from the Bishop sacrifice. At the same time, it appears that there is no clear way to get at the Black King. So what should White do? }
8. Nc3
{ Simply developing. In the absence of a clear mating attack, White can simply develop the Knight which offers many new ideas including Nd5+ and getting the a1 Rook out earlier in some lines.   8.Qd4  is almost a strong move but Black has a brilliant retort  8...c5!!  Ignoring the discovered attack!  9.Nxd7+  This double check is the only try White has  9...Ke7  With both the d4 Queen and d7 Knight hanging, Black will win back the Knight and material their material advantage.  10.Qe5+  Kxd7 }
8... Kxe5
{ 8...c5  9.Qf3+  Kxe5  10.Qf5+  Kd6  11.Bf4+  Ke7  If not for White's c3 Knight, Black's King has a good chance at survival. However, as it is...  12.Nd5+  Ke8  13.Qg6   8...c6  9.Qd4  c5  Black can try the same trick as we saw in the line 8. Qd4 c5. But this time, Black is down a tempo as White has Nc3. This makes all the difference.  10.Nxd7+  Ke7  11.Qe5+  Kxd7  12.Bf4  White is only one move away from castling long, giving Black no time to fend the attack off.   8...g6  9.Qf3+  Kxe5  10.Qf7  Black's King is stuck in the middle and must contend with Bf4+ and f4+. }
9. Qd5+ Kf6 10. Qf5+ Ke7 11. Nd5+
{ Thanks to the preparatory 8.Nc3, White is ready with a fierce attack. } 11...
Kd6 12. Bf4+ { Three pieces against the naked King should be sufficient. }
12... Kc6 13. Qe6+ Bd6 14. Nb4+ Kb6 15. Bxd6 cxd6 16. Qxd6+ Ka5 17. Qd5+
{ Forcing the King towards White's pawns, which will help with the mate. }
17... Kxb4 18. a3+ Ka4 19. b3# *

