[SetUp "1"]

{ What is the quickest way to get active ? } 8. O-O-O
{ Bringing a Rook to the d-file while unpinning the c3 Knight. The threats are hence d5 and Ne4. }
8... Bxc3 { Parrying the threat of Ne4. } 9. d5
{ Opening the position while forcing either Black's c6 Knight or c3 Bishop to an awkward square. }
9... Be5 10. dxc6 { Regaining the piece while remaining more active. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Advanced Exercises"]
[Black "Puzzle 1.2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/p1qp1ppp/1pP1pn2/2p1b1B1/2P5/PQ3N2/1P2PPPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 1 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black defended the Bishop with ...Qc7. How would Black try to untangle their position? }
11. g3
{ Even though Black's e5 Bishop is centrally placed, it is unprotected and somewhat trapped. Hence, Black would love to go ...Bf4+ to trade it off. g3 completely stops ...Bf4. Furthermore, White's light-squared Bishop is clearly most active on g2. }
11... Bd6 12. Bg2
{ White's monster light-squared Bishop is completely unchallenged. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Advanced Exercises"]
[Black "Puzzle 1.3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/p1q2ppp/1ppbpn2/2p3B1/2P5/PQ3NP1/1P2PPBP/2KR3R w kq - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The position is semi-open. How can we exploit the parts of the board that are open? }
13. Rxd6
{ Thanks to White's superior development, Black is somehow weak on both light squares @@StartBracket@@along the h1-a8 diagonal@@EndBracket@@ and dark squares @@StartBracket@@the pawns surrounding Black's King are all on light squares@@EndBracket@@. To capitalise on this, White must get rid of Black's main dark square defender, the Bishop. }
13... Qxd6 14. Rd1
{ Another benefit of the exchange sacrifice - there is no Bishop on d6 to block the d-file.   14.Bf4  This is not as strong as Rd1. We simply need to observe the squares controlled to understand why. Rd1 controls d6, d7 and d8. These are important squares regardless of where Black's Queen moves. On the other hand, Bf4 only controls d6 and c7, which are not maximally useful if Black hides on e7.  14...Qe7  15.Ne5  Threatening Bxc6 with a fork.  15...O-O  16.Nxc6  Qe8  The only safe square.  17.Bd6  White will win his exchange back, but not much more than that. }
14... Qc7
{ Let's consider the merits of Rd1 by looking at the line 14...Qe7   14...Qe7  15.Ne5  O-O  16.Nxc6  Qe8   16...Qc7  17.Bf4  Notice that White can always play Bf4 later if Black commits to Qc7.  17...Qb7  18.Bd6  The main threat is Ne7+ to unleash the g2 Bishop.  17.Rd8  The Rook on the d-file already makes itself very useful - the Queen is trapped. }
15. Bf4
{ Now that Black has played Qc7 and allowed White to play Bf4 for free, we will do just that. }
15... Qb7 16. Ne5
{ Our two Bishops and d1 Rook own all the open lines in the position.     16.Bd6?  Trying to stop Black from castling is not effective because he would have time to organise a defence on b7.  16...Qa6  17.Ne5  Bb7  White is better but the advantage isn't huge. }
*

