1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3 c5 6. a3 Ba5 7. Bg5 Nc6 8. O-O-O
{ Bringing a Rook to the d-file while unpinning the c3 Knight. The threats are hence d5 and Ne4. }
8... Bxc3 { Parrying the threat of Ne4. } 9. d5
{ Opening the position while forcing either Black's c6 Knight or c3 Bishop to an awkward square.   9.Qxc3  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Ne4  11.Bxd8  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Nxd8 }
9... Be5
{ 9...Na5  10.Qxc3  Ne4  Without any piece on d4, White can simply take on g7.  11.Qxg7  Black's Queen and Rook are both hanging. }
10. dxc6 { Now, Black must defend his e5 Bishop. } 10... Qc7
{ Even though Black's e5 Bishop is centrally placed, it is unprotected and somewhat trapped. Hence, Black would love to go ...Bf4+ to trade it off. }
11. g3
{ Stopping ...Bf4. Furthermore, White's light-squared Bishop is clearly most active on g2. }
11... Bd6 12. Bg2 dxc6
{ Thanks to White's superior development, Black is somehow weak on both light squares @@StartBracket@@along the h1-a8 diagonal@@EndBracket@@ and dark squares @@StartBracket@@the pawns surrounding Black's King are all on light squares@@EndBracket@@. To capitalise on this, White must get rid of Black's main dark square defender, the d6 Bishop. }
13. Rxd6 Qxd6 14. Rd1
{ Another benefit of the exchange sacrifice - there is no Bishop on d6 to block the d-file.   14.Bf4  This is not as strong as Rd1. We simply need to observe the squares controlled to understand why. Rd1 controls d6, d7 and d8. These are important squares regardless of where Black's Queen moves. On the other hand, Bf4 only controls d6 and c7, which are not maximally useful if Black hides on e7.  14...Qe7  15.Ne5  Threatening Bxc6 with a fork.  15...O-O  16.Nxc6  Qe8  The only safe square.  17.Bd6  White will win his exchange back, but not much more than that. }
14... Qc7
{ Let's consider the merits of Rd1 by looking at the line 14...Qe7   14...Qe7  15.Ne5  O-O  16.Nxc6  Qe8   16...Qc7  17.Bf4  White can always play Bf4 later if Black commits to Qc7.  17...Qb7  18.Bd6  The main threat is Ne7+ to unleash the g2 Bishop.  18...Kh8  The only way to prevent Ne7+.  19.Bxf8  17.Rd8  Notice how the Rook on the d-file already makes itself very useful - the Queen is trapped. }
15. Bf4
{ Now that Black has played Qc7 and allowed White to play Bf4 for free, we will do just that. }
15... Qb7 16. Ne5
{ Our two Bishops and d1 Rook own all the open lines in the position. } 16...
Bd7
{ There was no good way to stop Bxc6 without losing a bunch of material. Right now, Black is very weak on the light squares. Who is responsible for holding it together? }
17. Rxd7 { It's the d7 Bishop! c6 will certainly fall now. } 17... Nxd7 18.
Bxc6 Qa6 19. Nxd7 Qc8 20. Ba4 Ke7
{ Escaping the discovered attack along the a4-e8 diagonal. } 21. Qd3
{ Threatening Qd6! White is now going after dark squares. } 21... f6 22. Qd6+
Kf7 23. Ne5+
{ White simply wants to vacate the d7 square so that Bd7 is possible. } 23...
fxe5 24. Bd7 Qd8 25. Qxe6+ Kf8 26. Bxe5 { Threatening Bd6+. } 26... g6 27. Bf6
{ The Black Queen is hanging. If she leaves, Qe7+ will lead to mate. } *

