[Black "Game #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ This was a casual online blitz game between the great IM GothamChess and Oleg42YNWA  (2622)  . }
1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c6 3. Nf3 Bf5 4. e3 Nd7 5. Nh4 Be6
{ The h4 Knight and e6 Bishop have mutually worsened, but now White gets to push the f-pawn to reinforce control over the central dark squares. }
6. f4
{ Although White has moved the f-pawn in the opening, this move is not a mistake. This is because both Black's Queen and dark-squared Bishop are not in a position to take advantage of the weakened dark squares. }
6... Nh6 7. Bd3 Nc5 8. O-O Nxd3 9. cxd3 Nf5
{ The h4 Knight is challenged. What should White do? } 10. Nf3
{ Keeping the e6 Bishop passive!  The f5 Knight is not particularly difficult to handle. White does not have to worry about any light square weaknesses and the e4 pawn break is easy to execute.   10.Nxf5?  Bxf5  In contrast, if White had taken on f5, Black would have an active light-squared Bishop. This means that e4 pawn break would be tougher to realise and White must worry about the d3 pawn.  11.Qe2  Supporting e4.  11...Qb6  Preventing e4 while threatening Qa6 to attack d3.  12.d4  This pawn push relieves Black's pressure off the d3 and e3 pawns, but Black's light-squared Bishop is now unchallenged. Furthermore, White's dark-squared Bishop is blocked. }
10... h5
{ Neglecting development for some sketchy chances against White's King.   10...f6  Black must complete his Kingside development without dropping the g7 pawn. Hence, 10...f6 is a useful move to blunt our b2 Bishop.  11.e4  Nh6  12.f5  Bf7  13.Qe2  g6  This move is only made possible with 10...f6. Black can finally get his dark-squared Bishop out. }
11. e4 { White's pawns will overwhelm Black's centre. } 11... Qb6+ 12. Kh1 Nh6
13. f5 { The Bishop must un-develop. } 13... Bc8 14. Qe2 Ng4 15. h3
{ 15.exd5?  Now is not the time to open the position. White is not in a good position to take advantage of the e-file or defend f5.  15...Bxf5  Black is back in the game. }
15... e6 16. Nc3
{ Calmly completing development.   16.hxg4??  This is a mistake as it allows the h-file to open  16...hxg4+  17.Nh2  g3  Black will gain the piece back with interest. }
16... Be7 17. exd5 cxd5 18. Nxd5
{ Unnecessarily flashy, but White's advantage is so great that he can afford to open the position in this way.   18.Na4  Qa5  19.Bxg7  This is a simpler way to prevent Black from castling. }
18... exd5 19. Rae1
{ The idea is to prevent Black from castling, but there is a stronger way.   19.Ba3  Rae1 can wait ! Black will certainly lose a piece somehow.  19...Qf6  20.Rae1 }
19... O-O
{ Giving up the Bishop without a fight. Now White has an extra pawn and an excellent attack.   19...Qd6  Defending e7 while preventing White from piling up on e7 with Ba3. Now, White must play accurately to reach the following engine-generated draw line.  20.Bxg7  Rh7  21.f6  Nxf6  22.Bxf6  Qxf6  23.Nd4  Qg5  24.Nf3  Qf6 }
20. Qxe7 Nf2+ 21. Rxf2 { The start of a forced win. } 21... Qxf2 22. Bd4
{ White could have played this mating combination earlier.   22.Qxf8+  Kxf8  23.Ba3+  Kg8  24.Re8+  Kh7  25.Ng5+  Kh6  26.Nxf7+  Kh7  27.Rh8 }
22... Qg3 23. Be5 Qf2 24. Qxf8+ { A great find, especially in a blitz game! }
24... Kxf8 25. Bd6+ Kg8 26. Re8+ Kh7 27. Ng5+ Kh6 28. Nxf7+ Kh7 29. Rh8# *

