[White "9. Advanced Exercises"]
[Black "Game #4"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a game between Garry Kasparov and Ulf Andersson. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Who has benefitted from all the action on e4? Black had to move their Kingside Knight and their light-squared Bishop twice while White only had to move their Queenside Knight twice. At the end of the day, a pair of Knights are traded and only Black's light-squared Bishop remains alive and active. This means Black spent four tempi to get one piece developed and White spent two tempi to get no pieces developed.   Hence, one may conclude that White has a slight edge from this transaction. However, it should also be noted that White spent two tempi on the potentially irrelevant a3 and c4 moves. If those moves turn out to be useful, White would truly be advantageous. }
7. Nd2
{ White moves the Kingside Knight twice, but Black must return the favour with his light-squared Bishop. White is not concerned with blocking the c1 Bishop because he wants to fianchetto it. }
7... Bg6 8. g3 Nc6 9. e3 a6
{ This move is a little too slow.   9...Be7  followed by ...O-O would be more competitive. }
10. b4 b5 11. cxb5 axb5
{ Black gets to open the a-file and threaten ...Nxb4, but White can easily defend it with Bb2. Furthermore, Black must spend time defending b5. }
12. Bb2
{ 12.Bxb5?  Nxb4  All that remains is an open Queenside which Black can exploit more easily - All of his minor pieces are there to exploit the a3 weakness and more. }
12... Na7
{ The moves White invested on the Queenside proved useful given that Black had to effectively un-develop his Knight and by extension, the a8 Rook. It is now White's duty to strike. }
13. h4
{ Black must move either the f-pawn or h-pawn to prevent his Bishop from getting trapped with h5. The point of this zwischenzug is to weaken Black's light squares before opening up the position. }
13... h6
{ Another strong point of 13.h4 is that White conceals their intention to play d5 for the time being. If Black knew that White would go d5, he would have gone ...   13...f6!  This vacates the f7 square for the light-squared Bishop while blunting the a1-h8 diagonal, making White's dark-squared Bishop less useful.  14.d5  exd5  Black need not waste a tempo on moving his h-pawn and can already develop their dark-squared Bishop next move without fear of dropping g7. }
14. d5
{ Finally, opening the position after Black has already weakened the light squares on the Kingside a little. Both the a1-h8 diagonal and the e-file will be huge strengths for White. Now, Black will have some trouble developing the dark-squared Bishop while keeping g7 defended. }
14... exd5 15. Bg2 c6 16. O-O f6
{ Closing the a1-h8 diagonal, but now Black's light squares are tremendously weak - Only the g6 Bishop is holding down the fort. }
17. Re1 { Preparing e4. } 17... Be7 18. Qg4
{ Skewering g6 and g7.   18.e4?!  Not forcing enough. Black can return one pawn and quickly castle.  O-O  19.exd5  Bf7  20.dxc6  Nxc6  Comparatively speaking, Black manages to get a decent position. His King is safe and his pieces are not too passive. }
18... Kf7 { The only way to hold on to the material and the position. } 19. h5
Bh7 20. e4 { White is ready. } 20... dxe4 21. Bxe4
{ Our strategical targets are the light squares, and Black's h7 Bishop is the key defender. Hence, we seek to trade Bishops. In any case, our Bishop on g2 was not particularly useful.   21.Rxe4?  This move is only good if Black takes the Rook. Otherwise, White simply has a hard time bringing sufficient firepower to the light squares.  21...Re8  While White remains dominant, the advantage is less obvious.   21...Bxe4?  22.Bxe4  The attack is way too strong. }
21... Bxe4 22. Nxe4
{ Bringing more pieces towards the King.   22.Rxe4  is good too. } 22... Nc8
23. Rad1 { Developing the last piece with tempo by attacking d7. } 23... Ra7
24. Nxf6 { Softening the dark squares. } 24... gxf6
{ Now, both f6 and h6 have one less defender.  Black cannot allow the e-file to open and let White's Rooks become too active.   24...Bxf6  25.Qg6+  Kf8  26.Bxf6  gxf6   26...Qxf6  27.Re8  This is why Black needs a defender along the e-file.  27.Re6  Exploiting the pin on the d-file. Rxf6+ will be decisive. }
25. Qg6+ Kf8
{ As with most successful attacks, the rest is a matter of maneuvering the remaining pieces to the enemy King. }
26. Bc1 d5 27. Rd4 { Rook lift to g4! } 27... Nd6 28. Rg4 Nf7 29. Bxh6+ Ke8
{ 29...Nxh6  30.Qg7+  Ke8  31.Qxh8+  Kd7  32.Qxh6 } 30. Bg7
{ The h-pawn is running up the board, so Black resigned. } *

