{ For our final game, we have GM Alexander Graf vs GM Roman Slobodjan. } 1. e4
e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ This move is not very popular at the master level because Black does not challenge the centre greatly. }
4. Nxe4
{ Black has a smaller centre and has some difficulty getting their light-squared Bishop out. White, on the other hand, has virtually no problems. That said, Black is NOT losing to any decisive extent. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bd3 a6
{ Black is playing the less theoretically sound opening and should not waste time. Castling early should be the priority.   8...O-O }
9. Qe2 c5 10. dxc5 Qa5+ 11. c3 Qxc5 12. O-O b6
{ This move grants Black's light-squared Bishop the active b7 square, but it temporarily exposes the a8-h1 diagonal. This means Black cannot castle for another 2 moves. }
13. Ne5 Bb7
{ 13...O-O ??  As mentioned, the exposed a8-h1 diagonal prevents Black from castling.  14.Bxf6  Eliminating the defender of e4.  14...Bxf6  15.Qe4  Forking the a8 Rook and mate on h7. }
14. Rfe1
{ Reinforcing control over e4 to tactically discourage Black from castling. }
14... Qd5
{ Black could castle anyway, but the following forced line will take Black to a worse endgame.   14...O-O  15.Bxf6  Eliminating the defender of d7.  15...Bxf6  16.Nd7  Qd5  Black must move the Queen with a threat so that he would have time to save the f8 Rook.  17.Qe4  Defending mate while threatening mate on h7, forcing the Queen trade. This move was only made possible by 14.Rfe1.  17...Qxe4  18.Bxe4  Bxe4  19.Rxe4  Rfd8  20.Nxb6  Finally, snatching a pawn.  20...Rab8  21.Nc4  White's Queenside majority will decide the game. }
15. Qf1
{ The neatest way to defend the mate because White, yet again, tactically prevents Black from castling by unleashing the e1 Rook on the e4 square.   15.f3  O-O  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  17.Be4  Qxe5  18.Bxb7  Both Black's Queen and Rook are hanging, but Black can save the Queen first, then the Rook. Hence, the Queen needs to leave the e2 square on move 15 while defending g2.  18...Qxe2  19.Rxe2  Ra7 }
15... Bd6
{ 15...O-O  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  17.Be4  Qxe5  18.Bxb7  Both Black's Queen and Rook are hanging. }
16. Bf4 Qc5
{ 16...O-O  17.Rad1  It is tough for Black to save his pieces on the d-file. }
17. Rad1
{ Creating pressure on d6, thereby continuing to prevent Black from castling. }
17... Bc7
{ 17...O-O ?  18.Nd7  Nxd7  19.Bxd6  Gaining the piece back while forking Queen and Rook.  19...Qxd6  20.Bxh7+!  The point of 17.Rad1  20...Kxh7  21.Rxd6 }
18. b4 Qe7
{ Now, Black is ready to castle, but all that time spent on Black's Queen and dark-squared Bishop has allowed White to develop EVERY piece. All that's left is to find one or more weaknesses. What are Black's weaknesses ?   18...Qxc3  If this pawn is taken, White can skewer the c3 Queen and c7 Bishop.  19.Rc1 }
19. Bb5+
{ Black's weaknesses are the a4-e8 diagonal and his vulnerable King. The reason is that all our pieces are surrounding his uncastled King and the only clear way in is through the diagonal. }
19... axb5 20. Qxb5+ Kf8 21. Nd7+
{ Unleashing a discovered attack on Black's dark-squared Bishop to dramatically weaken Black's dark squares. }
21... Nxd7 22. Bxc7 { The threats are Bd6 pin or simply taking on d7. } 22...
Ke8 23. Bxb6
{ Now that the d7 Knight is pinned, White takes the b6 pawn to not only win material, but also allow the b5 Queen to go after the b7 Bishop. }
23... Rc8
{ 23...Ba6  is not a huge concern. White can consolidate with  24.Qa4  Bb7  25.Ba5  Black can no longer harass White's coordination. }
24. Bc5 { Threatening the e7 Queen and the b7 Bishop. } 24... Bc6
{ Saving the Bishop while counterattacking White's Queen. } 25. Qa6
{ Saving the Queen while counterattacking Black's Rook. } 25... Qd8
{ Saving the e7 Queen and defending the c8 Rook. It appears that Black is fine, for now. However, Black still cannot castle while White has easy control over the dark squares and the d-file. }
26. Rd6 Qc7 27. Rdxe6+
{ Black's pieces are not well coordinated to defend the King. Hence, the sacrifice. }
27... fxe6 28. Rxe6+ Kf7 29. Qc4
{ White will move the e6 Rook next with discovered check and there is nothing Black can do about it.   29.Re7+  followed by Qc4 is more direct. Otherwise, White's conversion was totally fine.  29...Kf6  30.Qc4  Nxc5   30...Rhf8  31.Qe6+  Kg5  32.Rxg7+  Kf4  33.Be3  31.Qf7+  Kg5  32.Rxc7 }
29... Nxc5 30. Rxc6+ Ke8 31. Rxc5 Qxc5 32. bxc5
{ With White's extra pawns against Black's uncoordinated pieces, the rest was an easy conversion for White. }
32... Ke7 33. Qe4+ Kf7 34. Qf5+ Ke7 35. g4
